1
00:00:08,878 --> 00:00:11,968
[ Foreboding music ]

2
00:02:27,930 --> 00:02:31,020
[ Radio announcer
speaking Russian ]

3
00:03:29,383 --> 00:03:31,776
[ American accent ]
Hi. Julie Schofield.

4
00:03:31,820 --> 00:03:32,864
Hello.

5
00:03:43,919 --> 00:03:46,095
That thing does work properly,
does it?

6
00:03:46,313 --> 00:03:47,662
Oh, it works just fine.

7
00:03:48,576 --> 00:03:50,839
I want my words preserved
for posterity.

8
00:03:51,274 --> 00:03:52,797
I won't miss a thing.

9
00:03:55,539 --> 00:03:57,802
-Drink?
-Thanks very much.

10
00:04:04,418 --> 00:04:06,811
No bourbon, I'm afraid.
Scotch.

11
00:04:06,855 --> 00:04:08,335
Scotch would be great.

12
00:04:09,423 --> 00:04:11,076
-Ice?
-Mm-hm.

13
00:04:11,338 --> 00:04:12,774
Yes, of course.

14
00:04:13,470 --> 00:04:14,689
I'm afraid so.

15
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:17,387
I've always wanted fame.

16
00:04:19,041 --> 00:04:20,172
I've always liked the idea

17
00:04:20,216 --> 00:04:21,739
of my name
going down in history.

18
00:04:22,218 --> 00:04:23,915
Going down as a spy
for Russia?

19
00:04:24,481 --> 00:04:26,222
Fame or infamy--
what does it matter?

20
00:04:26,440 --> 00:04:27,963
I shan't be forgotten.

21
00:04:30,444 --> 00:04:32,359
If my mother
could only see me now.

22
00:04:34,230 --> 00:04:35,753
The last of the few.

23
00:04:36,537 --> 00:04:37,973
It really was only a few?

24
00:04:38,669 --> 00:04:40,628
Oh, there were plenty
of people

25
00:04:40,671 --> 00:04:42,412
waiting to see
which way to jump.

26
00:04:43,065 --> 00:04:45,415
Things only had to go
a little differently and...

27
00:04:45,459 --> 00:04:46,677
well, you know.

28
00:04:47,809 --> 00:04:51,595
But, yes, in practice
we were just a few.

29
00:04:52,727 --> 00:04:53,728
A happy few.

30
00:04:54,685 --> 00:04:56,165
"Band of brothers."

31
00:04:57,384 --> 00:04:59,516
Shakespeare. "Henry V."

32
00:05:00,561 --> 00:05:02,563
Our most patriotic king.

33
00:05:04,478 --> 00:05:07,437
How big a band were you,
this "band of brothers"?

34
00:05:09,396 --> 00:05:11,789
Some things have
to remain secret, even now.

35
00:05:11,833 --> 00:05:12,921
You sure?

36
00:05:14,270 --> 00:05:15,619
Certain, no less.

37
00:05:17,708 --> 00:05:20,015
Background, dear lady,
is all I can give you.

38
00:05:21,495 --> 00:05:25,325
The whole delightful, utterly
despicable English background.

39
00:05:26,587 --> 00:05:29,372
JULIE: Well, I understand
the delightfulness, all right,

40
00:05:29,851 --> 00:05:31,853
but not why you had
to despise it.

41
00:05:32,419 --> 00:05:35,465
How someone of your class
and, well, background...

42
00:05:35,770 --> 00:05:37,075
Should want to kick it
in the teeth?

43
00:05:37,554 --> 00:05:38,381
Precisely.

44
00:05:41,210 --> 00:05:42,472
MAN: You've no idea what...

45
00:05:42,820 --> 00:05:45,257
life in England
in the 1930s was like.

46
00:05:46,258 --> 00:05:49,349
Treason and loyalty,
they're all relative, you know?

47
00:05:50,350 --> 00:05:51,525
Treason to what?

48
00:05:52,134 --> 00:05:53,570
Loyalty to whom?

49
00:05:53,614 --> 00:05:54,789
That's what matters.

50
00:05:56,443 --> 00:06:00,577
♪ I vow to thee, my country

51
00:06:01,230 --> 00:06:06,583
♪ All earthly things above

52
00:06:06,888 --> 00:06:12,633
♪ Entire and
whole and perfect ♪

53
00:06:12,894 --> 00:06:17,899
♪ The service of my love

54
00:06:18,900 --> 00:06:24,340
♪ The love that
asks no question ♪

55
00:06:24,688 --> 00:06:29,824
♪ The love that
stands the test ♪

56
00:06:30,477 --> 00:06:36,004
♪ That lays upon the altar

57
00:06:36,483 --> 00:06:41,836
♪ The dearest and the best

58
00:06:42,184 --> 00:06:48,016
♪ The love that never falters

59
00:06:48,364 --> 00:06:53,804
♪ The love
that pays the price ♪

60
00:06:54,631 --> 00:07:00,028
♪ The love that
makes undaunted ♪

61
00:07:00,463 --> 00:07:06,556
♪ The final sacrifice

62
00:07:08,297 --> 00:07:13,781
♪ And there's another country

63
00:07:14,172 --> 00:07:19,656
♪ I've heard of long ago

64
00:07:20,222 --> 00:07:25,880
♪ Most dear to them
that love her ♪

65
00:07:26,141 --> 00:07:30,972
♪ Most great
to them that know ♪

66
00:07:32,060 --> 00:07:33,322
[ Glass shatters ]

67
00:07:33,365 --> 00:07:37,457
♪ We may not
count her armies ♪

68
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:43,245
♪ We may not
see her King ♪

69
00:07:43,767 --> 00:07:49,294
♪ Her fortress is
a faithful heart ♪

70
00:07:49,338 --> 00:07:54,474
-[ Suspenseful music ]
-♪ Her pride is suffering

71
00:07:54,952 --> 00:07:56,040
[ Creaking ]

72
00:07:56,084 --> 00:08:01,089
♪ And soul by soul
and silently ♪

73
00:08:01,655 --> 00:08:07,008
♪ Her shining bounds increase

74
00:08:07,574 --> 00:08:13,449
♪ And her ways
are ways of gentleness ♪

75
00:08:13,493 --> 00:08:15,407
Martineau! Robbins!

76
00:08:15,451 --> 00:08:20,674
♪ And all her paths are peace

77
00:08:26,462 --> 00:08:30,858
They shall grow not old
as we that are left grow old.

78
00:08:31,511 --> 00:08:35,732
Age shall not weary them,
nor the years condemn.

79
00:08:36,907 --> 00:08:38,866
At the going down of the sun,

80
00:08:39,214 --> 00:08:40,911
and in the morning,

81
00:08:40,955 --> 00:08:43,044
we will remember them.

82
00:08:43,958 --> 00:08:46,177
ALL: We will remember them.

83
00:08:49,398 --> 00:08:50,747
[ Bell chiming ]

84
00:08:50,791 --> 00:08:52,749
Want to come and have lunch?
My parents are down.

85
00:08:52,793 --> 00:08:54,446
That's very nice of you. Thanks.

86
00:08:54,490 --> 00:08:56,100
-MAN 1: You were laughing.
-MAN 2: I was not.

87
00:08:56,144 --> 00:08:58,146
-MAN 1: Giggling, then.
-MAN 2: I didn't utter a sound.

88
00:08:58,189 --> 00:09:00,757
You were giggling silently.
I couldn't concentrate at all.

89
00:09:00,801 --> 00:09:01,628
Jaffed.

90
00:09:04,152 --> 00:09:06,371
Even a crusty old Tory like you,
Devenish,

91
00:09:06,415 --> 00:09:08,591
must be able to see that it's
absolutely ludicrous

92
00:09:08,635 --> 00:09:10,506
for 400 boys to line up and blub
for a lot of people

93
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:11,594
they never even knew.

94
00:09:11,638 --> 00:09:12,900
What do you mean
they didn't know?

95
00:09:12,943 --> 00:09:14,554
Who only died
in a businessman's war

96
00:09:14,597 --> 00:09:15,598
because they were
too damn stupid

97
00:09:15,642 --> 00:09:16,773
to shoot their superior officers

98
00:09:16,817 --> 00:09:18,383
and start a revolution
like the Russians.

99
00:09:19,428 --> 00:09:21,430
They werethe superior officers,
weren't they?

100
00:09:22,213 --> 00:09:23,824
We could all see
who youwere thinking about.

101
00:09:24,389 --> 00:09:27,218
Wharton! Wharton!

102
00:09:28,263 --> 00:09:30,134
A lovely glass of sherry...

103
00:09:35,923 --> 00:09:37,098
Yes, Barclay?

104
00:09:37,141 --> 00:09:38,403
Take these round
to all the houses, please.

105
00:09:38,752 --> 00:09:40,710
I want one on every noticeboard
before lunch.

106
00:09:40,754 --> 00:09:41,755
Yes, Barclay.

107
00:09:43,626 --> 00:09:45,846
What you forget is
all those people died for us.

108
00:09:45,889 --> 00:09:47,978
They died for their class.
You aretheir class.

109
00:09:48,370 --> 00:09:50,067
It's damn silly
to pretend you're not.

110
00:09:50,546 --> 00:09:52,200
You're always
trying to be different.

111
00:09:52,243 --> 00:09:53,418
What's wrong with
being different?

112
00:09:53,462 --> 00:09:54,332
Well, you are.

113
00:09:55,595 --> 00:09:57,335
I mean, you want to be elected
to be a God,

114
00:09:57,379 --> 00:09:58,336
don't you, Devenish?

115
00:09:58,380 --> 00:10:00,208
-Yes.
-They're different.

116
00:10:00,251 --> 00:10:01,688
That's not what I mean.

117
00:10:04,038 --> 00:10:05,648
[ Sighs ]
You wait.

118
00:10:05,692 --> 00:10:07,302
My waistcoats are
going to be the most different

119
00:10:07,345 --> 00:10:08,346
you've ever seen.

120
00:10:08,390 --> 00:10:10,000
Why an intelligent person
like you

121
00:10:10,044 --> 00:10:11,088
should want to be part

122
00:10:11,132 --> 00:10:12,481
of a self-perpetuating
oligarchy--

123
00:10:12,524 --> 00:10:13,874
It's a pity you have
to be a prefect

124
00:10:13,917 --> 00:10:15,136
before you can be elected,

125
00:10:15,484 --> 00:10:17,007
else I'd be wearing one now.

126
00:10:17,268 --> 00:10:19,488
Oh, you'll make it next time.
Menzies will see to that.

127
00:10:20,054 --> 00:10:21,621
Will l? That's the question.

128
00:10:21,664 --> 00:10:23,144
I expect so.

129
00:10:26,060 --> 00:10:27,409
Would you like to do the honors,
Barclay?

130
00:10:27,452 --> 00:10:28,497
Yes, of course.

131
00:10:30,368 --> 00:10:33,154
Well, I must say I think
that's the best service yet.

132
00:10:33,197 --> 00:10:34,590
Yes, yes.

133
00:10:34,938 --> 00:10:38,028
[ Indistinct chatter ]

134
00:10:46,515 --> 00:10:49,692
[ Boys shouting ]

135
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:50,606
[ Piano playing ]

136
00:11:12,454 --> 00:11:13,281
Boys!

137
00:11:14,761 --> 00:11:16,023
Any of you seen Martineau?

138
00:11:21,158 --> 00:11:23,421
[ Shouting resumes ]

139
00:11:23,465 --> 00:11:26,511
[ Melancholy music ]

140
00:12:19,608 --> 00:12:23,220
[ Bell chimes ]

141
00:12:26,267 --> 00:12:28,269
Bennett, do
pull yourself together.

142
00:12:34,754 --> 00:12:36,364
Funny even as though he
was there.

143
00:12:38,845 --> 00:12:39,846
Not yet.

144
00:12:41,151 --> 00:12:45,503
Any moment now,
the great oak doors of Longford

145
00:12:45,547 --> 00:12:47,810
shall swing open
on their rusty hinges...

146
00:12:47,854 --> 00:12:49,594
That door does need oiling.
[ Chuckles ]

147
00:12:50,204 --> 00:12:51,379
BENNETT:
...and the glorious vision

148
00:12:51,422 --> 00:12:52,728
will step forth here.

149
00:12:53,207 --> 00:12:54,382
He'll stand a moment,

150
00:12:54,425 --> 00:12:56,514
winsomely framed
in the tumescent archway.

151
00:12:57,211 --> 00:12:58,125
Doing what?

152
00:12:58,647 --> 00:12:59,779
Sniffing the wind.

153
00:13:00,692 --> 00:13:02,259
Like a dappled deer.

154
00:13:02,303 --> 00:13:04,174
-[ Laughs ]
-Oh, my God.

155
00:13:04,479 --> 00:13:07,961
And then... then he'll shoot
a tender yet burning,

156
00:13:08,222 --> 00:13:09,876
soft yet passionate glance

157
00:13:09,919 --> 00:13:12,182
across the 300 yards
of sacred turf,

158
00:13:12,226 --> 00:13:13,357
hoping against hope

159
00:13:13,923 --> 00:13:15,577
that I shall be there
to receive it.

160
00:13:16,752 --> 00:13:17,579
Hmm.

161
00:13:18,667 --> 00:13:19,799
And I shall lay my heart
at his feet.

162
00:13:20,669 --> 00:13:21,844
Must have enormous feet

163
00:13:21,888 --> 00:13:23,324
if they'll stretch
from Longford's to here.

164
00:13:23,367 --> 00:13:25,282
-Hello Menzies, want a peek?
-MENZIES: Thank you, no.

165
00:13:25,326 --> 00:13:26,153
You seen Martineau?

166
00:13:27,458 --> 00:13:28,677
No, I'm afraid I only have eyes
for one person

167
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:30,157
in the entire world.

168
00:13:30,200 --> 00:13:32,333
-Any of you?
-Probably with his parents.

169
00:13:32,812 --> 00:13:34,161
I don't think they came down.

170
00:13:34,596 --> 00:13:36,554
Still, never mind.
Thanks.

171
00:13:36,598 --> 00:13:38,687
No, thank you
for the good-humored restraint

172
00:13:38,730 --> 00:13:40,776
with which you exercise
your power, Menzies.

173
00:13:43,257 --> 00:13:45,607
It's not only not fair,
it's not even sensible.

174
00:13:45,650 --> 00:13:46,651
Come on, Judd!

175
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:49,219
Our parents spend hundreds
of pounds a year

176
00:13:49,263 --> 00:13:50,830
sending us to this prison
so we can be educated

177
00:13:51,091 --> 00:13:53,049
and we spend the entire time
playing games.

178
00:13:53,093 --> 00:13:53,963
Quite right too.

179
00:13:54,790 --> 00:13:56,139
Games are good for Bolsheviks.

180
00:13:56,183 --> 00:13:57,532
Teach you a bit of team spirit.

181
00:13:57,793 --> 00:13:58,881
You could be quite good
at cricket

182
00:13:58,925 --> 00:13:59,795
if you'd only try.

183
00:14:00,187 --> 00:14:01,666
JUDD: I don't want to try.

184
00:14:01,710 --> 00:14:03,103
I want to be left alone
so I can get on with my work.

185
00:14:05,540 --> 00:14:06,933
[ Indistinct chatter ]

186
00:14:09,587 --> 00:14:11,938
I hope you're not taking those
binos out of house, Bennett.

187
00:14:12,721 --> 00:14:15,028
Then you hope in vain, Fowler.

188
00:14:15,811 --> 00:14:18,205
Farcical's given me permission
to use them for nature study.

189
00:14:18,814 --> 00:14:19,641
Who?

190
00:14:20,424 --> 00:14:21,338
Farcical.

191
00:14:22,905 --> 00:14:24,428
If you mean the Housemaster,
kindly use his proper name.

192
00:14:24,472 --> 00:14:25,473
-You didn't.
-What?

193
00:14:25,908 --> 00:14:26,909
Use his proper name.

194
00:14:27,649 --> 00:14:29,390
His proper name is
Mr. Farquharson.

195
00:14:29,433 --> 00:14:30,957
Are you trying to be clever
or something?

196
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:33,220
I don't have to try.
I am clever.

197
00:14:33,698 --> 00:14:36,266
I've half a mind to ask Barclay
for permission to beat you.

198
00:14:36,310 --> 00:14:38,225
Well, you've half a mind,
we can all agree on that.

199
00:14:38,268 --> 00:14:40,792
-[ Laughing ]
-[ Yells ] Quiet!

200
00:14:42,185 --> 00:14:43,926
Get changed, everybody.

201
00:14:43,970 --> 00:14:45,406
Anyone late
for the house matches

202
00:14:45,449 --> 00:14:47,408
will be up before Barclay
for six strokes.

203
00:14:47,451 --> 00:14:48,888
ALL: Ooh!

204
00:14:49,801 --> 00:14:50,846
[ Laughing ]

205
00:14:55,068 --> 00:14:56,547
What you have to grasp,
Devenish,

206
00:14:56,591 --> 00:14:57,679
is that Fowler is
precisely what

207
00:14:57,722 --> 00:14:59,289
this school was designed
to produce.

208
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:04,033
Not empire builders--
dear me, no.

209
00:15:04,077 --> 00:15:05,817
Building empires
needs imagination.

210
00:15:06,514 --> 00:15:08,951
-Empire rulers.
-Oh, do dry up.

211
00:15:09,256 --> 00:15:11,649
Fowler will go straight
from the King's African Rifles

212
00:15:11,693 --> 00:15:13,347
into the Colonial Service--
you'll see.

213
00:15:13,390 --> 00:15:15,740
-He'll end up with an OBE.
-And syphilis.

214
00:15:16,045 --> 00:15:17,525
Bennett, do you mind?

215
00:15:17,568 --> 00:15:19,744
He'll catch it off
a little native girl

216
00:15:19,788 --> 00:15:23,792
who he'll visit after dark
in her steamy primeval hut.

217
00:15:24,575 --> 00:15:26,490
And when he gets back
to his mildewed little wife

218
00:15:26,534 --> 00:15:28,275
in Bexhill-on-the-Sea,

219
00:15:28,318 --> 00:15:29,450
he won't be able
to look her in the face!

220
00:15:29,493 --> 00:15:30,973
So, he'll turn her over
and...

221
00:15:31,017 --> 00:15:32,540
For heaven's sake!

222
00:15:32,583 --> 00:15:34,107
Serves her right
for marrying an imperialist

223
00:15:34,150 --> 00:15:35,543
and an exploiter.

224
00:15:35,586 --> 00:15:37,240
There's nothing wrong
with the Colonial Service...

225
00:15:37,284 --> 00:15:38,415
"It's a perfectly
decent career."

226
00:15:38,459 --> 00:15:39,634
Shut up!

227
00:15:39,677 --> 00:15:41,201
There is nothing decent
about colonialism.

228
00:15:41,592 --> 00:15:43,855
I don't see why you have
to be against everything.

229
00:15:43,899 --> 00:15:46,119
I'm not. I'm for revolution.

230
00:15:47,033 --> 00:15:48,077
All right, everyone!

231
00:15:49,339 --> 00:15:51,559
Umpires for Longford's
versus Chancellors?

232
00:15:51,820 --> 00:15:53,953
Oh, me, please.
Me and Judd.

233
00:15:54,649 --> 00:15:55,606
All right.

234
00:15:59,088 --> 00:16:00,220
I don't want to go and umpire.

235
00:16:00,960 --> 00:16:02,396
Yes, you do. Come along.

236
00:16:08,489 --> 00:16:11,405
[ Scattered applause ]

237
00:16:18,760 --> 00:16:21,806
[ Melancholy music ]

238
00:16:44,394 --> 00:16:45,526
MAN: Umpire!

239
00:16:46,701 --> 00:16:48,094
Umpire, that was a wide.

240
00:16:48,877 --> 00:16:49,965
No, it wasn't.

241
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:51,445
I couldn't possibly have
reached that.

242
00:16:51,488 --> 00:16:53,229
Course you could.
You just didn't try.

243
00:16:53,273 --> 00:16:55,449
It was practically
outside the white line.

244
00:16:55,884 --> 00:16:57,538
Are you arguing with the umpire?

245
00:16:58,234 --> 00:17:00,845
Because arguing with the umpire
is not school practice.

246
00:17:00,889 --> 00:17:02,195
At least, it might be
in your house

247
00:17:02,238 --> 00:17:03,674
but it certainly isn't in ours.

248
00:17:03,718 --> 00:17:05,415
And since we beat you last week,
you can just shut up!

249
00:17:14,207 --> 00:17:15,295
Play!

250
00:17:23,303 --> 00:17:24,173
How's that!

251
00:17:24,434 --> 00:17:25,348
Out!

252
00:17:26,610 --> 00:17:29,178
[ Scattered applause ]

253
00:17:33,226 --> 00:17:34,314
MAN: I think we should have
rung the muffled peal

254
00:17:34,357 --> 00:17:35,402
after the dedication.

255
00:17:35,445 --> 00:17:36,577
I don't see why we didn't.

256
00:17:36,620 --> 00:17:38,100
MAN 2: Because we're not
good enough yet.

257
00:17:38,144 --> 00:17:40,059
You don't have to be good
to run a muffled peal.

258
00:17:40,537 --> 00:17:41,408
It's muffled.

259
00:17:41,669 --> 00:17:42,496
No one can really tell.

260
00:17:43,627 --> 00:17:44,846
I'll muffle you if
you don't shut up.

261
00:17:45,455 --> 00:17:46,282
[ Indistinct chatter ]

262
00:17:52,114 --> 00:17:55,422
Out! You lot-- go!
Out, all of you.

263
00:17:55,683 --> 00:17:57,380
Spungin, you get a master.
Now!

264
00:17:57,424 --> 00:18:00,862
MAN: Jesus, God! Did you see?
That was Martineau.

265
00:18:00,905 --> 00:18:02,429
[ Indistinct chatter ]

266
00:18:15,964 --> 00:18:17,052
[ Slams door ]

267
00:18:40,858 --> 00:18:41,685
[ Sighs ]

268
00:18:42,208 --> 00:18:43,296
This place.

269
00:18:46,777 --> 00:18:48,257
This place!

270
00:18:56,222 --> 00:18:58,267
These things should be
left to the Gods.

271
00:19:00,008 --> 00:19:01,270
He'd never have done it

272
00:19:01,314 --> 00:19:03,185
if he hadn't been sent
to see the headmaster.

273
00:19:03,925 --> 00:19:05,622
He knew that meant expulsion.

274
00:19:05,970 --> 00:19:07,972
Yes, but once a master had
caught him, Delahay,

275
00:19:08,016 --> 00:19:09,235
it was out of our hands.

276
00:19:10,671 --> 00:19:12,455
Especially as it was
with a man from another house.

277
00:19:12,499 --> 00:19:13,891
The Gods could have
dealt with it.

278
00:19:13,935 --> 00:19:15,154
That's what we're here for.

279
00:19:15,458 --> 00:19:17,547
Prefects handle house matters.

280
00:19:17,591 --> 00:19:19,419
The Gods deal with
everything else.

281
00:19:19,810 --> 00:19:21,943
And masters should mind
their own business.

282
00:19:22,248 --> 00:19:24,859
Even the mighty Gods
can't expel people, Delahay.

283
00:19:24,902 --> 00:19:26,121
Who needs people expelled?

284
00:19:26,513 --> 00:19:28,123
You wouldn't have
let Martineau stay?

285
00:19:28,167 --> 00:19:29,646
DELAHEY: Of course.

286
00:19:29,690 --> 00:19:31,213
But he wouldn't have been able
to sit down for a week

287
00:19:31,257 --> 00:19:32,649
after the Gods had
finished with him.

288
00:19:32,693 --> 00:19:34,825
But if we start expelling
everyone who indulges--

289
00:19:34,869 --> 00:19:35,913
Yes. Well, there we are,
aren't we?

290
00:19:37,437 --> 00:19:38,568
The tone of this whole house
has simply gone to pieces

291
00:19:38,612 --> 00:19:40,657
and you, Delahay,
are mainly responsible.

292
00:19:40,701 --> 00:19:42,659
-Fowler, please.
-Yes. Shut up, Fowler.

293
00:19:42,703 --> 00:19:44,357
But it's precisely attitudes
like that--

294
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:45,532
Will you shut up!

295
00:19:52,278 --> 00:19:53,366
Now, we're all, I know,

296
00:19:53,409 --> 00:19:54,845
very distressed about
what's happened.

297
00:19:55,803 --> 00:19:56,891
Personally...

298
00:19:57,326 --> 00:19:58,588
[ Sighs ]

299
00:19:58,632 --> 00:19:59,937
well, I've always tried
to make everyone feel

300
00:19:59,981 --> 00:20:01,591
he can come to me at any time,

301
00:20:01,635 --> 00:20:02,679
whatever the problem.

302
00:20:04,072 --> 00:20:05,204
But he must have been desperate.

303
00:20:06,727 --> 00:20:08,598
It probably wouldn't have
made any difference.

304
00:20:08,642 --> 00:20:11,210
But if he'd talked to me,
to you... anyone!

305
00:20:16,084 --> 00:20:16,998
However,

306
00:20:18,826 --> 00:20:20,828
we have to try and overcome
our personal feelings.

307
00:20:21,220 --> 00:20:23,222
And remember
our responsibility to the house.

308
00:20:23,265 --> 00:20:24,614
Hear, hear.

309
00:20:24,658 --> 00:20:26,268
We don't want people rushing off
confessing things,

310
00:20:26,312 --> 00:20:28,444
which, quite frankly, they'd
do better to keep to themselves.

311
00:20:28,488 --> 00:20:29,750
If people have things
to confess,

312
00:20:29,793 --> 00:20:31,055
I think they
should confess them.

313
00:20:31,665 --> 00:20:33,667
A thorough clear out is what
this house needs.

314
00:20:33,971 --> 00:20:36,322
Thing is, I would like there
to be a House here next term

315
00:20:36,365 --> 00:20:37,584
for me to be Head of.

316
00:20:37,801 --> 00:20:39,760
Well, I'm sure it's not nearly
on that scale.

317
00:20:40,848 --> 00:20:42,937
Well, anyway, wouldn't you like
to start with a clean house?

318
00:20:43,285 --> 00:20:44,765
Quite frankly, I doubt if
such a thing

319
00:20:44,808 --> 00:20:46,027
as a clean house exists,

320
00:20:46,549 --> 00:20:48,159
in this school or any other.

321
00:20:50,597 --> 00:20:52,642
What about a special session
of house prayers?

322
00:21:17,711 --> 00:21:19,713
FOWLER: Almighty
and most merciful Father.

323
00:21:20,366 --> 00:21:22,846
ALL: "Almighty
and most merciful Father,

324
00:21:23,369 --> 00:21:26,850
"we have erred and strayed
from thy ways like lost sheep.

325
00:21:27,547 --> 00:21:28,896
"We have followed too much

326
00:21:29,157 --> 00:21:31,768
the devices and desires
of our own hearts."

327
00:21:32,421 --> 00:21:34,380
[ Prayer continues ]

328
00:21:41,822 --> 00:21:43,214
If you ask me, it all comes of

329
00:21:43,258 --> 00:21:45,173
having masters who
aren't old boys.

330
00:21:47,697 --> 00:21:48,655
I see.

331
00:21:49,786 --> 00:21:51,527
Well, an old boy
would have more sense

332
00:21:51,571 --> 00:21:53,703
than to go prowling around
gymnasium changing room.

333
00:21:56,010 --> 00:21:57,838
Everybody knows what
goes on there.

334
00:22:01,929 --> 00:22:04,453
Look, you'd better
watch yourself, Bennett.

335
00:22:05,367 --> 00:22:07,456
Discretion is going to be
the better part of valor

336
00:22:07,500 --> 00:22:08,457
around here.

337
00:22:08,501 --> 00:22:09,545
Wouldn't you say?

338
00:22:22,253 --> 00:22:23,603
May I go and talk to Judd,
please?

339
00:22:24,560 --> 00:22:26,040
If you think you
can get a word in.

340
00:22:26,562 --> 00:22:27,998
[ Prayer continues ]

341
00:22:35,441 --> 00:22:38,400
"Thou shalt not lie with mankind
as with womankind."

342
00:22:38,966 --> 00:22:40,271
"lt is abomination."

343
00:22:41,185 --> 00:22:43,231
"Neither shalt thy lie
with any beast

344
00:22:43,274 --> 00:22:45,146
to defile thyself therewith."

345
00:22:45,842 --> 00:22:48,454
"Neither shall any woman
stand before a beast

346
00:22:48,497 --> 00:22:50,064
to lie down there too."

347
00:22:50,717 --> 00:22:51,805
"lt is confusion."

348
00:22:53,197 --> 00:22:56,157
"Defile not ye yourselves
in any of these things."

349
00:22:59,378 --> 00:23:01,423
-Alone at last!
-Get off.

350
00:23:04,208 --> 00:23:05,035
[ Sighs ]

351
00:23:06,167 --> 00:23:07,473
-I'll get you one day.
-No, you won't.

352
00:23:07,516 --> 00:23:09,083
Yes, I will. Everyone gives in
in the end.

353
00:23:09,344 --> 00:23:10,606
It's Bennett's Law.

354
00:23:10,650 --> 00:23:13,043
-I won't give in.
-Well, you're not normal.

355
00:23:19,876 --> 00:23:21,138
BENNETT: My God,
that was quick. Who did it?

356
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:22,401
Matron.

357
00:23:34,413 --> 00:23:36,023
Poor Martineau.

358
00:23:45,206 --> 00:23:47,034
The reason everyone gives in
in the end

359
00:23:48,339 --> 00:23:49,950
is they get lonely
doing it on their own.

360
00:23:50,907 --> 00:23:52,431
-They long for company.
-Well, I don't.

361
00:23:53,606 --> 00:23:55,129
Not your sort, anyway.

362
00:23:55,172 --> 00:23:57,261
That's why my mother's marrying
this awful Colonel person.

363
00:23:57,784 --> 00:23:58,698
Arthur.

364
00:24:00,090 --> 00:24:02,484
It couldn't just possibly be
that she loves him?

365
00:24:02,528 --> 00:24:03,529
Out of the question.

366
00:24:04,834 --> 00:24:06,357
He's got one of those
awful little moustaches.

367
00:24:06,662 --> 00:24:07,794
He's ghastly.

368
00:24:09,143 --> 00:24:10,884
Almost as much of a loather
as my father was.

369
00:24:11,145 --> 00:24:12,842
You mean even you
would draw the line?

370
00:24:14,017 --> 00:24:15,192
Don't be revolting.

371
00:24:15,671 --> 00:24:16,629
He's a grown-up.

372
00:24:17,368 --> 00:24:18,195
Of course.

373
00:24:19,240 --> 00:24:20,415
And it's all just
a passing phase.

374
00:24:20,459 --> 00:24:22,939
Exactly. Just like you
being a communist.

375
00:24:22,983 --> 00:24:23,810
Ha, ha.

376
00:24:26,813 --> 00:24:28,118
-Judd...
-Hmm?

377
00:24:30,207 --> 00:24:33,167
-You and your usherette.
-What about her?

378
00:24:35,735 --> 00:24:37,084
Is it really so different?

379
00:24:37,563 --> 00:24:38,477
From what?

380
00:24:39,826 --> 00:24:40,870
Boys.

381
00:24:42,263 --> 00:24:44,308
Well, how would I know?
I've only ever had a girl.

382
00:24:45,527 --> 00:24:46,485
What is it, Wharton?

383
00:24:47,790 --> 00:24:48,835
I don't know what to do
about Spungin's water.

384
00:24:49,096 --> 00:24:50,010
Leave him to pass it
on his own...

385
00:24:51,185 --> 00:24:52,403
and pour it out
and go to bed.

386
00:24:52,447 --> 00:24:54,362
He makes a terrible fuss
if his water's cold.

387
00:24:54,928 --> 00:24:56,669
He said he'd report me
to Barclay.

388
00:24:57,321 --> 00:24:59,193
Then go fill up the jug
with new hot water,

389
00:24:59,236 --> 00:25:00,673
bring it back to the dorm,

390
00:25:00,716 --> 00:25:02,718
cover it with a flannel,
and leave it by Spungin's bed,

391
00:25:02,762 --> 00:25:03,545
all right?

392
00:25:03,850 --> 00:25:04,981
Thanks, Judd.

393
00:25:07,593 --> 00:25:10,073
[ Faucet running ]

394
00:25:10,378 --> 00:25:12,336
-Hurry up, Wharton.
-Yes, Delahay.

395
00:25:15,470 --> 00:25:17,646
God, "Das Kapital"
looks difficult.

396
00:25:19,039 --> 00:25:20,344
Well, I haven't found anything

397
00:25:20,388 --> 00:25:21,911
I couldn't
understand eventually.

398
00:25:22,738 --> 00:25:24,392
And if they taught us
any economics here

399
00:25:24,697 --> 00:25:26,133
instead of Tudors
and bloody Stuarts...

400
00:25:28,091 --> 00:25:29,876
Marx should be a set book
for the sixth.

401
00:25:30,659 --> 00:25:31,834
They shouldn't leave us

402
00:25:31,878 --> 00:25:32,705
to fight our way through it
on our own.

403
00:25:34,707 --> 00:25:36,535
And under the blankets.

404
00:25:39,625 --> 00:25:40,539
[ Sighs ]

405
00:25:41,888 --> 00:25:43,150
Barclay confiscated
another torch last night.

406
00:25:43,193 --> 00:25:44,891
-How many is that?
-Twelve.

407
00:25:45,631 --> 00:25:47,197
Twelve torches taken away

408
00:25:47,241 --> 00:25:49,460
to stop me getting the education
I'm supposed to be here for.

409
00:25:50,592 --> 00:25:53,552
God, if our parents only knew
what actually went on here.

410
00:25:54,465 --> 00:25:55,554
They do know.

411
00:25:57,120 --> 00:25:58,078
The fathers, anyway.

412
00:25:58,687 --> 00:26:01,385
[ Solemn music ]

413
00:26:49,042 --> 00:26:50,304
Bennett, what the hell
are you doing?

414
00:26:51,174 --> 00:26:52,262
Go to bed.

415
00:26:52,306 --> 00:26:54,961
[ Choir sings ]

416
00:26:56,919 --> 00:26:57,746
[ Door slams ]

417
00:26:58,791 --> 00:27:03,056
♪ My kingdom sails

418
00:27:03,317 --> 00:27:07,408
♪ and grows forever

419
00:27:07,669 --> 00:27:13,457
♪ Dear Lord, thy creatures all

420
00:27:13,501 --> 00:27:17,418
♪ Lord, I swear

421
00:27:18,898 --> 00:27:20,551
[ Bell chiming ]

422
00:27:29,996 --> 00:27:33,042
[ Intriguing music plays ]

423
00:28:34,582 --> 00:28:36,149
What's this?

424
00:28:36,192 --> 00:28:37,977
I'm very sorry, Fowler,
I thought l--

425
00:28:38,020 --> 00:28:39,718
Juniors aren't required
to think, Wharton.

426
00:28:39,761 --> 00:28:41,284
They are required
to obey orders

427
00:28:41,328 --> 00:28:43,286
and I told you
to make cup shine.

428
00:28:43,330 --> 00:28:44,157
Yes, Fowler.

429
00:28:45,375 --> 00:28:46,202
Well...

430
00:28:47,769 --> 00:28:49,553
...not bad except
for that smear.

431
00:28:50,293 --> 00:28:51,164
Get it off.

432
00:28:52,295 --> 00:28:53,253
Yes, Fowler.

433
00:29:01,391 --> 00:29:02,479
BENNETT: You know, if you are
going to be

434
00:29:02,523 --> 00:29:03,480
in the south of France,

435
00:29:03,524 --> 00:29:04,612
you might as well look around

436
00:29:04,655 --> 00:29:06,048
for a nice little villa
for August.

437
00:29:06,614 --> 00:29:07,615
Might l?

438
00:29:08,964 --> 00:29:10,792
Why not just
extend the honeymoon?

439
00:29:11,880 --> 00:29:13,142
I could pop down
on the Blue Train

440
00:29:13,186 --> 00:29:14,404
just as soon as school's over.

441
00:29:14,448 --> 00:29:15,492
I see.

442
00:29:17,059 --> 00:29:19,366
I only want to bring one friend.
It won't be too expensive.

443
00:29:20,106 --> 00:29:22,369
I don't think Arthur
would like Judd, darling.

444
00:29:22,412 --> 00:29:23,936
I don't mean Judd, darling.

445
00:29:25,111 --> 00:29:27,287
Anyway, Arthur thinks
everyone under the age of 18

446
00:29:27,330 --> 00:29:29,202
is either a pinko or a pansy,

447
00:29:29,245 --> 00:29:30,986
so it won't make much difference
who I bring, will it?

448
00:29:31,030 --> 00:29:32,205
[ Laughing ]

449
00:29:33,380 --> 00:29:36,862
You know, I'm awfully worried.

450
00:29:38,037 --> 00:29:39,778
You see,
it is an established fact

451
00:29:40,779 --> 00:29:43,520
that people who go around
suspecting vice in others

452
00:29:43,564 --> 00:29:45,305
are highly suspect themselves.

453
00:29:45,871 --> 00:29:48,656
But Arthur's the most normal man
I've ever known!

454
00:29:48,917 --> 00:29:50,092
What better disguise?

455
00:29:50,136 --> 00:29:51,702
Listen, there's still time
to call it off.

456
00:29:52,181 --> 00:29:53,356
Come on, let's stop the car.

457
00:29:54,227 --> 00:29:56,229
You really shouldn't
joke about it, Guy.

458
00:29:57,534 --> 00:29:59,058
Not after that poor boy.

459
00:30:00,711 --> 00:30:02,278
I suppose he
was dreadfully unpopular.

460
00:30:02,801 --> 00:30:04,977
Martineau? No.

461
00:30:05,368 --> 00:30:07,153
Well, I should thought
a boy like that--

462
00:30:07,196 --> 00:30:08,807
Very well, better off dead,
no doubt about it.

463
00:30:09,285 --> 00:30:12,593
Well, I have known
one or two of-- of those.

464
00:30:12,898 --> 00:30:14,334
And they're never very happy,
you know?

465
00:30:14,377 --> 00:30:15,901
Mummy!

466
00:30:15,944 --> 00:30:18,904
Oh, they can be very amusing,
but, uh-- Oh, here we are!

467
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,732
[ Birds singing ]

468
00:30:34,136 --> 00:30:37,226
[ Organ music
plays in distance ]

469
00:30:57,943 --> 00:31:00,946
[ Indistinct chatter ]

470
00:31:23,794 --> 00:31:25,057
[ Laughing ]

471
00:31:25,100 --> 00:31:26,754
If you ask me,
public schools go on too long.

472
00:31:26,797 --> 00:31:28,799
[ Laughs ]
Arthur means the fees.

473
00:31:28,843 --> 00:31:29,931
It's not just the fees.

474
00:31:29,975 --> 00:31:30,889
I mean, look at Guy.

475
00:31:32,107 --> 00:31:33,282
He's not a boy anymore.
He's a young man.

476
00:31:33,326 --> 00:31:35,458
-Aren't you, old chap?
-Rather.

477
00:31:35,502 --> 00:31:36,938
Well then, I think you
should leave

478
00:31:36,982 --> 00:31:39,506
at the end of this term.
Take a job for a year or two.

479
00:31:39,549 --> 00:31:40,376
Go around the world.

480
00:31:40,855 --> 00:31:41,943
You must be mad.

481
00:31:41,987 --> 00:31:43,423
School's just getting
to the good bit.

482
00:31:43,466 --> 00:31:45,599
ARTHUR: I think you need
to find out a bit about life

483
00:31:45,642 --> 00:31:46,905
before you go up
to the varsity.

484
00:31:46,948 --> 00:31:47,862
I second that.

485
00:31:49,255 --> 00:31:50,517
Why not the army?

486
00:31:50,560 --> 00:31:52,127
Why not, indeed? First class.

487
00:31:52,475 --> 00:31:54,869
I mean, one learns
so much about life

488
00:31:54,913 --> 00:31:55,826
in the army.

489
00:31:55,870 --> 00:31:57,828
-Yes.
-Killing people.

490
00:32:01,093 --> 00:32:02,268
Excuse me.

491
00:32:03,051 --> 00:32:04,313
Mummy!

492
00:32:06,750 --> 00:32:08,404
How dare you talk like that?!

493
00:32:09,362 --> 00:32:11,016
How dare you plan
to send me around the world

494
00:32:11,059 --> 00:32:12,147
without even consulting me?

495
00:32:12,191 --> 00:32:13,583
-It's all right, lvy.
-Oh, excuse me.

496
00:32:13,627 --> 00:32:15,281
It was only an idea, darling.

497
00:32:15,324 --> 00:32:16,891
It was just
that Arthur thought--

498
00:32:16,935 --> 00:32:17,718
Arthur!

499
00:32:19,024 --> 00:32:20,112
We only want to do what's
best for you, Guy.

500
00:32:20,764 --> 00:32:22,070
If either of you
seriously thinks

501
00:32:22,114 --> 00:32:23,506
I would leave now,

502
00:32:23,550 --> 00:32:25,465
after 10 years of hard labor

503
00:32:25,508 --> 00:32:27,380
in the salt mines
of prep and public school.

504
00:32:27,423 --> 00:32:29,686
-You want to stay?
-I'm going to be a God, Mummy.

505
00:32:29,991 --> 00:32:30,949
What?

506
00:32:30,992 --> 00:32:31,819
[ Scoffs ]

507
00:32:33,038 --> 00:32:34,039
The school elite.
The creme de la creme.

508
00:32:34,474 --> 00:32:36,084
Oh, yes. Of course.

509
00:32:36,128 --> 00:32:38,391
It's the only thing that's made
the last 10 years endurable--

510
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:40,219
the thought that one day,

511
00:32:40,262 --> 00:32:41,611
I'm gonna be top
of the whole stinking heap!

512
00:32:41,655 --> 00:32:43,178
Well, if that's how you feel,
darling.

513
00:32:46,312 --> 00:32:48,140
I really must get back
to my wedding.

514
00:32:58,715 --> 00:33:00,543
[ Horn blares ]

515
00:33:14,688 --> 00:33:17,778
[ Gentle piano music ]

516
00:33:40,366 --> 00:33:41,802
Would you care for a drink, sir?

517
00:33:42,455 --> 00:33:45,023
Ah, yes. A glass of sherry,
thank you.

518
00:33:45,066 --> 00:33:46,285
Very good, sir.

519
00:34:11,005 --> 00:34:11,962
[ Chuckles ]

520
00:34:12,006 --> 00:34:13,051
Gosh, you are brave.

521
00:34:14,487 --> 00:34:15,879
Did you think I wouldn't come?

522
00:34:16,445 --> 00:34:21,059
I, um, didn't know.
I hoped you would.

523
00:34:25,367 --> 00:34:26,890
Well...

524
00:34:28,283 --> 00:34:29,241
...here I am.

525
00:34:33,375 --> 00:34:37,075
I, um, hope you're hungry.
I'm ravenous.

526
00:34:37,118 --> 00:34:39,773
I've had nothing to eat but
a bit of caviar and toast

527
00:34:39,816 --> 00:34:40,817
all day long.

528
00:34:41,166 --> 00:34:43,646
-Doesn't sound bad.
-Oh! It's awful.

529
00:34:44,734 --> 00:34:46,214
Listen, l, um...

530
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:49,261
...I can't call you Harcourt.

531
00:34:49,304 --> 00:34:51,263
-My name is Guy.
-I know.

532
00:34:52,351 --> 00:34:53,482
I found out.

533
00:34:54,831 --> 00:34:57,182
-Mine's James.
-James.

534
00:34:58,879 --> 00:34:59,706
[ Chuckles ]

535
00:35:00,837 --> 00:35:02,361
That's a very nice name.

536
00:35:04,189 --> 00:35:05,364
You know,
I nearly lost my nerve.

537
00:35:05,407 --> 00:35:06,408
[ Laughs ]

538
00:35:07,714 --> 00:35:09,498
I passed a couple of masters
on the way here.

539
00:35:09,542 --> 00:35:11,109
Oh, don't worry about them.
They won't come in here.

540
00:35:11,152 --> 00:35:12,066
They can't afford to.

541
00:35:13,285 --> 00:35:17,115
Listen, then, do you like
smoked salmon?

542
00:35:17,506 --> 00:35:18,594
I love it.

543
00:35:20,422 --> 00:35:21,945
I-- I love...

544
00:35:23,338 --> 00:35:26,036
...I-- I love food and drink
and...

545
00:35:27,995 --> 00:35:28,822
[ Snickers ]

546
00:35:29,953 --> 00:35:31,651
Should we get terribly,
terribly drunk?

547
00:35:31,694 --> 00:35:33,479
-If you like!
-[ Laughs ]

548
00:35:34,132 --> 00:35:36,830
The only thing is, though,
sometimes when I get drunk, l--

549
00:35:37,178 --> 00:35:39,137
I say things I shouldn't.

550
00:35:41,574 --> 00:35:44,185
Still, we ought to have
something to celebrate with,

551
00:35:44,229 --> 00:35:45,099
oughtn't we?

552
00:35:46,361 --> 00:35:47,623
WAITER: Your sherry, sir.

553
00:35:48,581 --> 00:35:49,930
Are you ready to order?

554
00:35:50,844 --> 00:35:51,845
Ah, not yet.

555
00:35:51,888 --> 00:35:52,802
Bring me the wine list,
would you?

556
00:35:53,238 --> 00:35:54,282
Here we are, sir.

557
00:35:56,241 --> 00:35:59,026
We've a nice little hock,
if you care for hock, sir.

558
00:35:59,244 --> 00:36:00,593
No, no, no-- champagne.

559
00:36:00,941 --> 00:36:02,029
I've been drinking it all day
and it doesn't do

560
00:36:03,161 --> 00:36:03,422
to mix one's drinks.

561
00:36:04,597 --> 00:36:05,772
What's the best champagne
you've got?

562
00:36:06,425 --> 00:36:07,904
The Moet, I suppose, sir.

563
00:36:17,044 --> 00:36:19,220
It's been a most
unfortunate affair, of course,

564
00:36:19,264 --> 00:36:20,526
but on the whole,

565
00:36:20,569 --> 00:36:22,049
the school has not
come out of it too badly.

566
00:36:22,876 --> 00:36:24,573
For that, we must be
extremely grateful

567
00:36:24,617 --> 00:36:27,141
to Barclay and Henderson

568
00:36:27,185 --> 00:36:30,013
for the admirable way they've
handled their respective houses

569
00:36:30,057 --> 00:36:32,842
through what could have been
a most serious crisis.

570
00:36:32,886 --> 00:36:34,322
ALL: Hear, hear.

571
00:36:36,803 --> 00:36:39,240
We all know how quickly
scandal can spread.

572
00:36:39,284 --> 00:36:40,850
As a matter of fact,
my father won't have

573
00:36:40,894 --> 00:36:43,157
anyone in the firm from Harrow
because of what he's heard.

574
00:36:43,940 --> 00:36:45,203
Well, I can't imagine him

575
00:36:45,246 --> 00:36:46,769
wanting anyone from Harrow,
anyway.

576
00:36:47,770 --> 00:36:51,034
But we do still have to
make it absolutely clear

577
00:36:51,078 --> 00:36:52,384
to the outside world

578
00:36:53,167 --> 00:36:55,213
this was
a completely isolated incident.

579
00:36:55,256 --> 00:36:57,302
I cannot emphasize
too strongly--

580
00:36:57,737 --> 00:36:59,129
that nothing even remotely
like it

581
00:36:59,391 --> 00:37:01,349
can ever be allowed
to occur again.

582
00:37:03,264 --> 00:37:04,352
All right?

583
00:37:07,007 --> 00:37:09,183
GUY: My real father died
when I was 14.

584
00:37:10,402 --> 00:37:11,881
JAMES: How awful.

585
00:37:14,580 --> 00:37:16,103
It was the Easter hol's.

586
00:37:17,278 --> 00:37:19,237
I was reading one night
in my bed when...

587
00:37:20,281 --> 00:37:21,804
I heard the most
peculiar noise--

588
00:37:21,848 --> 00:37:22,675
a sort of...

589
00:37:23,632 --> 00:37:25,155
a sort of muffled squeaking.

590
00:37:26,505 --> 00:37:28,420
Couldn't think what it was,
at first.

591
00:37:31,901 --> 00:37:34,948
Sounded... trapped or something.

592
00:37:36,341 --> 00:37:39,735
So l-- I went down the passage

593
00:37:39,779 --> 00:37:42,521
and it seemed to be coming
from my parents' room

594
00:37:42,564 --> 00:37:44,218
and there was a light
under the door so...

595
00:37:45,263 --> 00:37:46,176
...I assumed...

596
00:37:46,829 --> 00:37:48,222
none of my business.

597
00:37:48,614 --> 00:37:49,571
Gosh.

598
00:37:51,007 --> 00:37:53,445
Then l-- I distinctly heard
my mother say, "Help."

599
00:37:56,361 --> 00:37:57,840
[ Whispers ]
Help.

600
00:37:59,015 --> 00:38:00,495
It was terribly eerie.

601
00:38:01,975 --> 00:38:06,284
Complete silence
and there it was again. "Help."

602
00:38:07,894 --> 00:38:10,244
I-- I didn't know what to do.

603
00:38:11,114 --> 00:38:11,941
No.

604
00:38:13,421 --> 00:38:15,815
I went down the passage
and I knocked loudly on the door

605
00:38:15,858 --> 00:38:16,903
and I said, "Are you all right?"

606
00:38:16,946 --> 00:38:18,470
And she said,
"Guy, quick, help."

607
00:38:20,167 --> 00:38:22,474
She sounded
absolutely at her last gasp.

608
00:38:23,431 --> 00:38:25,128
So I--I went in.

609
00:38:28,262 --> 00:38:30,830
Listen, are you sure you
really want to hear this?

610
00:38:31,526 --> 00:38:34,616
No. No, not if you don't
want to tell me.

611
00:38:36,096 --> 00:38:37,619
No, no, I do.

612
00:38:40,274 --> 00:38:41,754
My...

613
00:38:43,103 --> 00:38:45,671
my father had--
had a heart attack.

614
00:38:49,065 --> 00:38:52,242
-Right in the middle of--
-No!

615
00:38:53,809 --> 00:38:55,463
Happens all the time,
apparently.

616
00:38:57,509 --> 00:38:59,380
Well, what better way to go
for the man,

617
00:38:59,424 --> 00:39:00,512
but for my mother...

618
00:39:01,121 --> 00:39:04,124
Well... she was trapped.

619
00:39:04,777 --> 00:39:07,649
How absolutely incredible!

620
00:39:08,084 --> 00:39:09,042
It was awful.

621
00:39:10,348 --> 00:39:12,306
My mother kept her eyes closed
the whole time.

622
00:39:13,786 --> 00:39:15,004
Only wish I could've done--
I was--

623
00:39:16,136 --> 00:39:17,529
It was so embarrassing.

624
00:39:18,443 --> 00:39:20,053
God, it must have been.

625
00:39:20,836 --> 00:39:22,490
She never really
looked me in the eye again.

626
00:39:24,710 --> 00:39:27,930
See... I always hated him.

627
00:39:27,974 --> 00:39:31,020
He was...he was vile.

628
00:39:32,718 --> 00:39:34,372
My mother...

629
00:39:35,764 --> 00:39:37,723
Always been very fond
of my mother.

630
00:39:39,594 --> 00:39:42,728
But, well...

631
00:39:43,293 --> 00:39:45,470
things haven't been
quite the same

632
00:39:45,513 --> 00:39:46,514
between us since...

633
00:39:47,428 --> 00:39:48,821
...since then.

634
00:39:51,476 --> 00:39:53,391
Perhaps, that's why
she married again?

635
00:39:55,958 --> 00:39:57,438
Perhaps it is.

636
00:39:58,700 --> 00:40:00,093
Never thought about that.

637
00:40:14,324 --> 00:40:15,151
[ Sighs ]

638
00:40:17,023 --> 00:40:19,329
You know what I'd like
to do sometime?

639
00:40:21,723 --> 00:40:23,595
Ride around Europe
on a bicycle.

640
00:40:25,814 --> 00:40:26,641
With a tent.

641
00:40:27,903 --> 00:40:29,470
Sharing it with someone
you really like.

642
00:40:29,514 --> 00:40:31,037
Hmm.

643
00:40:32,821 --> 00:40:34,214
I've never spent the night
with anyone.

644
00:40:36,085 --> 00:40:38,087
-Have you?
-No.

645
00:40:39,915 --> 00:40:40,916
Must be wonderful.

646
00:40:43,353 --> 00:40:44,442
Have you ever been in love?

647
00:40:46,922 --> 00:40:49,359
No. Have you?

648
00:40:50,752 --> 00:40:51,579
No.

649
00:40:54,277 --> 00:40:55,104
[ Sniffs ]

650
00:40:55,888 --> 00:40:57,411
Must get in.

651
00:41:10,729 --> 00:41:12,470
-[ Whispers ] Goodnight.
-Goodnight.

652
00:41:24,830 --> 00:41:25,657
[ Sighs ]

653
00:41:30,009 --> 00:41:31,489
Fetch!

654
00:41:32,968 --> 00:41:36,276
BOY:
Come here. Come here!

655
00:41:56,426 --> 00:41:57,384
Susie!

656
00:41:58,994 --> 00:42:00,082
Come here!

657
00:42:06,480 --> 00:42:07,307
Sit!

658
00:42:32,114 --> 00:42:33,072
[ Grunts ]

659
00:42:34,073 --> 00:42:35,161
[ Grunts again ]

660
00:42:48,870 --> 00:42:51,264
All right, Bennett,
I've got you this time.

661
00:42:52,265 --> 00:42:54,702
Oh! God, I thought you
were Fowler.

662
00:42:54,746 --> 00:42:57,357
[ Grunting ]

663
00:42:58,140 --> 00:42:59,011
Hmm!

664
00:42:59,664 --> 00:43:00,490
[ Closing window ]

665
00:43:01,535 --> 00:43:03,581
That drainpipe's
a bloody disgrace.

666
00:43:03,885 --> 00:43:05,583
I must have a word
with the Housemaster.

667
00:43:05,626 --> 00:43:07,062
Sh!

668
00:43:08,803 --> 00:43:09,717
Tommy...

669
00:43:11,937 --> 00:43:13,634
May I call you Tommy, Tommy?

670
00:43:14,026 --> 00:43:14,853
If you want.

671
00:43:16,681 --> 00:43:18,639
Oh! I'm in love.

672
00:43:19,597 --> 00:43:21,033
That's not exactly news.

673
00:43:21,076 --> 00:43:23,601
Well, I-- I don't mean in love.
I mean--

674
00:43:25,820 --> 00:43:26,778
I mean in love.

675
00:43:27,605 --> 00:43:28,562
You're drunk.

676
00:43:29,955 --> 00:43:31,739
You know, till now,
it's just been a game but...

677
00:43:33,698 --> 00:43:34,829
...now!

678
00:43:35,264 --> 00:43:36,396
What are you doing here?

679
00:43:37,832 --> 00:43:38,790
I thought you didn't have to
be back till tomorrow?

680
00:43:39,617 --> 00:43:40,661
And why are you
dressed like a God?

681
00:43:41,270 --> 00:43:43,577
Um, practicing for next term.

682
00:43:44,317 --> 00:43:45,579
Well, you'd better be careful

683
00:43:45,623 --> 00:43:46,580
not to get any more food
on that waistcoat then.

684
00:43:47,886 --> 00:43:49,061
-It's grubby already.
-Oh, damn the waistcoat!

685
00:43:49,104 --> 00:43:50,062
I've been waiting for this
ever since my...

686
00:43:50,540 --> 00:43:52,020
Nothing's ever going to
be as good again

687
00:43:52,064 --> 00:43:53,718
till I'm ambassador in Paris.

688
00:43:53,761 --> 00:43:54,675
Don't be so pathetic.

689
00:43:56,459 --> 00:43:58,592
Life is ladders, Tommy,
that's all.

690
00:43:58,636 --> 00:43:59,549
[ Sighs ]

691
00:43:59,593 --> 00:44:00,899
Prep school to here.

692
00:44:01,421 --> 00:44:02,944
First Form to sixth.

693
00:44:02,988 --> 00:44:05,425
Second assistant
junior undersecretary

694
00:44:05,468 --> 00:44:06,818
to ambassador in Paris.

695
00:44:06,861 --> 00:44:09,472
Sir Guy Bennett, KCVO, KCMG.

696
00:44:09,821 --> 00:44:10,952
Contemptible sycophant

697
00:44:10,996 --> 00:44:12,562
in the service
of the bourgeoisie.

698
00:44:13,085 --> 00:44:13,912
What?

699
00:44:15,304 --> 00:44:16,001
It's what Lenin called
the renegade Karl Kautsky.

700
00:44:16,392 --> 00:44:17,306
Did he indeed?

701
00:44:18,699 --> 00:44:20,135
Because he substituted
eclecticism and sophistry

702
00:44:20,179 --> 00:44:21,136
for dialectics.

703
00:44:21,180 --> 00:44:22,616
Oh, well, that is bad.

704
00:44:22,921 --> 00:44:24,400
Groveling about the kings
and queens,

705
00:44:24,444 --> 00:44:25,271
walking backwards!

706
00:44:25,575 --> 00:44:26,838
Kissing hands.

707
00:44:28,404 --> 00:44:30,493
You're utterly imbued
with the spirit of servility,

708
00:44:30,537 --> 00:44:31,407
that's what he'd have said.

709
00:44:32,539 --> 00:44:33,279
You mean he wouldn't have
liked me?

710
00:44:33,932 --> 00:44:34,759
No.

711
00:44:35,760 --> 00:44:37,500
What about James?
Who's James?

712
00:44:37,805 --> 00:44:39,328
Harcourt. His name's James.

713
00:44:41,287 --> 00:44:42,723
Quite frankly,

714
00:44:42,767 --> 00:44:43,419
I don't think he'd have
cared much for the pair of you.

715
00:44:44,594 --> 00:44:47,162
God! First, they take away
my torches.

716
00:44:47,467 --> 00:44:50,078
Then when I take my life--
or at least my bum-- in my hands

717
00:44:50,122 --> 00:44:51,689
and creep here to do some work,
they send me you.

718
00:44:52,646 --> 00:44:53,821
This place is impossible.

719
00:44:54,169 --> 00:44:55,693
-Goodnight.
-Goodnight.

720
00:44:59,697 --> 00:45:03,396
♪ Who stole my heart away

721
00:45:03,439 --> 00:45:04,266
Huh!

722
00:45:05,528 --> 00:45:08,183
♪ Who makes me dream all day

723
00:45:09,228 --> 00:45:13,188
♪ Dreams I know will
never come true ♪

724
00:45:13,885 --> 00:45:17,802
♪ Seems as though
I'll ever be blue ♪

725
00:45:20,543 --> 00:45:23,590
[ Indistinct chatter ]

726
00:45:27,159 --> 00:45:29,074
All up!

727
00:45:38,648 --> 00:45:39,606
Who's last?

728
00:45:41,303 --> 00:45:42,130
Wharton.

729
00:45:42,957 --> 00:45:44,132
Find Menzies and ask him

730
00:45:44,176 --> 00:45:45,568
to come to me in the garden,
right away.

731
00:45:45,830 --> 00:45:48,006
-Yes, Barclay.
-Go on!

732
00:45:58,886 --> 00:46:00,932
-BOY: How's that!
-[ Scattered applause ]

733
00:46:03,325 --> 00:46:05,719
-Jim, good.
-What is it?

734
00:46:08,635 --> 00:46:10,506
I'm sorry, I've just discovered
something awful.

735
00:46:11,638 --> 00:46:14,336
Mr. Farquharson's thinking
of asking Fowler to stay on.

736
00:46:14,859 --> 00:46:16,643
To be Head of House
instead of you.

737
00:46:17,252 --> 00:46:18,079
What?

738
00:46:19,211 --> 00:46:19,994
You see, the house isn't
going to have

739
00:46:20,038 --> 00:46:20,908
enough prefects next term.

740
00:46:21,430 --> 00:46:22,736
Why not? What do you mean?

741
00:46:23,084 --> 00:46:25,434
It'll only be you and Bennett.
Two's not enough.

742
00:46:26,261 --> 00:46:28,002
-What about Devenish?
-He's leaving.

743
00:46:28,046 --> 00:46:30,788
His parents take a very dim view
of the Martineau business.

744
00:46:31,527 --> 00:46:32,702
They want him to

745
00:46:32,746 --> 00:46:33,965
go to agricultural college
straightaway.

746
00:46:34,704 --> 00:46:36,445
And as Fowler's
a year senior to you

747
00:46:37,098 --> 00:46:39,057
and as Judd refuses
to be a prefect...

748
00:46:39,100 --> 00:46:40,014
Judd!

749
00:46:40,710 --> 00:46:41,799
Unless you can get him

750
00:46:41,842 --> 00:46:43,365
to take a more
responsible attitude,

751
00:46:43,409 --> 00:46:44,366
you're a man short, Jim.

752
00:46:44,932 --> 00:46:46,064
Fat chance!

753
00:46:47,935 --> 00:46:49,110
I'm terribly sorry.

754
00:46:50,895 --> 00:46:52,157
He's your only hope.

755
00:46:53,419 --> 00:46:54,246
[ Scattered applause ]

756
00:47:12,960 --> 00:47:14,657
The answer is no.

757
00:47:19,662 --> 00:47:21,012
I wish you'd reconsider.

758
00:47:21,577 --> 00:47:22,709
I wish you'd let me work.

759
00:47:25,364 --> 00:47:27,670
Look, I wouldn't ask you to do
anything you didn't want to do.

760
00:47:29,107 --> 00:47:30,978
You just have to go through
the motions, that's all.

761
00:47:31,761 --> 00:47:35,461
Prep duty, dorm, roll call.
Nothing, really.

762
00:47:36,244 --> 00:47:39,421
Menzies, have you the makings
of a politician?

763
00:47:40,161 --> 00:47:41,859
I'm only speaking
as one friend to another.

764
00:47:41,902 --> 00:47:43,469
You have! Well, well.

765
00:47:45,210 --> 00:47:46,428
Look, you don't want Fowler
to be Head of House

766
00:47:46,472 --> 00:47:47,603
any more than I do.

767
00:47:47,647 --> 00:47:49,040
He'll make your life
a complete misery.

768
00:47:49,344 --> 00:47:50,302
Too bad.

769
00:47:51,520 --> 00:47:52,782
But I still refuse
to collaborate

770
00:47:52,826 --> 00:47:53,871
with a system of oppression.

771
00:47:54,436 --> 00:47:55,916
Oh, for God's sake!

772
00:48:04,882 --> 00:48:05,926
GUY: Oh, my God!

773
00:48:10,539 --> 00:48:11,366
I can't look.

774
00:48:12,454 --> 00:48:13,760
Are you all right, Bennett?

775
00:48:14,456 --> 00:48:15,718
Shall I get Matron?

776
00:48:15,762 --> 00:48:18,373
No. It was his smile.
It-- it made me dizzy.

777
00:48:20,723 --> 00:48:22,987
Everything beautiful is
slightly lopsided.

778
00:48:23,901 --> 00:48:25,815
There's a hollow
at the base of his throat

779
00:48:25,859 --> 00:48:27,034
that makes me want to

780
00:48:27,078 --> 00:48:28,427
pour honey all over him
and lick it off--

781
00:48:28,470 --> 00:48:29,863
-Bennett!
-Hmm?

782
00:48:29,907 --> 00:48:31,212
Wharton, this washing up
was supposed to

783
00:48:31,256 --> 00:48:32,126
be finished 10 minutes ago.

784
00:48:32,431 --> 00:48:33,736
Bennett, you come with me.

785
00:48:38,306 --> 00:48:39,829
Have you completely lost
your mind?!

786
00:48:40,830 --> 00:48:41,875
Yes, actually.

787
00:48:41,919 --> 00:48:43,094
After all that's happened,

788
00:48:43,137 --> 00:48:44,356
you talk like that
in front of a junior?!

789
00:48:44,399 --> 00:48:45,879
-He doesn't understand.
-Of course he does!

790
00:48:46,662 --> 00:48:48,447
You'd better take a pull
on yourself, Guy.

791
00:48:48,490 --> 00:48:49,622
I'd rather do it with you.

792
00:48:51,493 --> 00:48:52,755
For God's sake, will you stop?

793
00:48:54,235 --> 00:48:56,281
You've got to start showing
a little responsibility.

794
00:48:57,151 --> 00:48:58,892
What on earth are you
talking about?

795
00:48:59,458 --> 00:49:00,633
You don't know
what's going on.

796
00:49:01,112 --> 00:49:02,809
-Devenish may be leaving.
-Well?

797
00:49:03,288 --> 00:49:05,333
Fowler may be going to stay on
as Head of House.

798
00:49:09,424 --> 00:49:10,251
[ Sighs ]

799
00:49:13,472 --> 00:49:14,560
It can't be true...

800
00:49:15,039 --> 00:49:16,954
Unfortunately, it can.

801
00:49:18,259 --> 00:49:19,521
I need your help, Guy.

802
00:49:21,001 --> 00:49:22,524
It's all Judd's fault
for refusing to be a prefect.

803
00:49:23,351 --> 00:49:24,483
I want you to talk to him.

804
00:49:24,526 --> 00:49:25,832
You're much more his friend
than I am.

805
00:49:27,660 --> 00:49:29,314
Shouldn't think
there's a hope in hell.

806
00:49:29,357 --> 00:49:30,445
Well, there must be.

807
00:49:31,751 --> 00:49:33,057
Remember, if Fowler becomes
Head of House,

808
00:49:33,100 --> 00:49:34,623
he certainly won't put you up
for the Gods.

809
00:49:35,929 --> 00:49:37,278
I'm relying on you, Guy.

810
00:49:39,019 --> 00:49:40,760
Prove your worth for once.

811
00:50:02,477 --> 00:50:04,044
Alright, Devenish,
let's have a look.

812
00:50:10,833 --> 00:50:11,878
Not bad.

813
00:50:12,400 --> 00:50:13,488
Not bad at all.

814
00:50:15,186 --> 00:50:17,057
-Bennett.
-Where?

815
00:50:17,927 --> 00:50:19,842
Don't be silly.
Let me see your uniform.

816
00:50:26,849 --> 00:50:28,025
Well, it won't do.

817
00:50:29,026 --> 00:50:30,375
It won't do at all.

818
00:50:30,418 --> 00:50:31,550
What's wrong with it?

819
00:50:31,593 --> 00:50:33,030
Do you call those creases?

820
00:50:34,205 --> 00:50:36,772
Well, I'm not very handy
with the iron, actually.

821
00:50:36,816 --> 00:50:38,992
Do them again.
Do everything again.

822
00:50:39,036 --> 00:50:40,950
I'm not having you
let down the whole house.

823
00:50:41,951 --> 00:50:43,692
Won't be the whole house,
Fowler, I mean...

824
00:50:44,432 --> 00:50:46,130
...the juniors aren't
in the corps.

825
00:50:46,173 --> 00:50:47,261
Nor is Judd.

826
00:50:47,305 --> 00:50:48,697
Don't mention Judd to me.

827
00:50:49,263 --> 00:50:50,090
Judd?

828
00:50:51,961 --> 00:50:53,441
Judd.

829
00:50:55,182 --> 00:50:58,229
Judd, Judd, Judd, Judd, Judd...

830
00:50:59,491 --> 00:51:01,014
The moon shines bright.

831
00:51:03,408 --> 00:51:05,062
On such a night as this...

832
00:51:06,324 --> 00:51:09,066
...when the sweet wind
did gently kiss the trees

833
00:51:09,109 --> 00:51:10,371
and they did make no noise...

834
00:51:13,548 --> 00:51:15,811
..on such a night, Bennett,
methinks,

835
00:51:15,855 --> 00:51:17,900
mounted the Gascoigne walls

836
00:51:18,423 --> 00:51:21,556
and sighed his soul toward
the Longford tents...

837
00:51:23,950 --> 00:51:25,952
...where Harcourt
lay that night.

838
00:51:37,094 --> 00:51:38,225
I can't do it.

839
00:51:40,358 --> 00:51:42,099
I just cannot be a prefect.

840
00:51:45,319 --> 00:51:46,320
Why not?

841
00:51:47,234 --> 00:51:49,062
I do have my reputation,
you know?

842
00:51:49,106 --> 00:51:50,107
[ Scoffs ]
Your what?

843
00:51:51,586 --> 00:51:53,588
I'm a school joke,
I quite realize that.

844
00:51:56,591 --> 00:51:58,767
But I am, don't you think,
a respected joke?

845
00:52:00,856 --> 00:52:02,510
I do at least stick
to my principles.

846
00:52:02,554 --> 00:52:03,598
People appreciate that.

847
00:52:05,209 --> 00:52:06,514
If I abandoned them now...

848
00:52:09,126 --> 00:52:10,083
No. Sorry.

849
00:52:10,605 --> 00:52:12,216
You don't care
what people think.

850
00:52:12,694 --> 00:52:14,087
About me personally, no.

851
00:52:14,696 --> 00:52:16,568
But they'll say
it was all a fake.

852
00:52:17,003 --> 00:52:19,353
No... No.

853
00:52:19,701 --> 00:52:20,920
Say, "That's what we
said all along.

854
00:52:20,963 --> 00:52:22,574
It's all just a form
of showing off."

855
00:52:22,617 --> 00:52:23,836
On the contrary,

856
00:52:23,879 --> 00:52:26,578
they'll see the means
justifying the ends.

857
00:52:27,535 --> 00:52:28,971
What could be more communist
than that?

858
00:52:29,233 --> 00:52:30,495
They'll think it was all a fake.

859
00:52:31,887 --> 00:52:33,672
They'll think all communists
are fake.

860
00:52:35,021 --> 00:52:36,457
That's what they say
about Stalin.

861
00:52:36,979 --> 00:52:38,981
Now, what's that Stalin
got to do with it?

862
00:52:39,852 --> 00:52:41,810
That man is sweating blood
night and day

863
00:52:41,854 --> 00:52:43,725
to drag his country
into the 20th century

864
00:52:43,769 --> 00:52:46,250
and create a whole new concept
of society at the same time.

865
00:52:46,554 --> 00:52:48,165
I can't stand it when
people sneer at him.

866
00:52:48,208 --> 00:52:50,210
-Jokes about the Tsar...
-Quick! Quick!

867
00:53:01,961 --> 00:53:03,180
Thought I might find you here.

868
00:53:09,534 --> 00:53:12,014
It's all right.
I couldn't sleep either.

869
00:53:13,277 --> 00:53:15,409
That bloody dog of Wharton's
gets on my nerves.

870
00:53:17,281 --> 00:53:18,499
I should like to
go walkies myself.

871
00:53:19,108 --> 00:53:20,109
Want to come?

872
00:53:21,415 --> 00:53:22,808
I'm not exactly dressed
for walking, actually.

873
00:53:24,549 --> 00:53:25,506
I was working.

874
00:53:26,290 --> 00:53:27,160
Well...

875
00:53:28,422 --> 00:53:32,034
I won't disturb you.
Would you like my torch?

876
00:53:33,166 --> 00:53:34,211
It is yours.

877
00:53:37,910 --> 00:53:38,737
Thanks.

878
00:53:40,129 --> 00:53:42,001
This drainpipe's
still all right, isn't it?

879
00:53:42,044 --> 00:53:43,132
Afraid I can't tell you.

880
00:53:45,309 --> 00:53:46,875
-Barclay...
-Yes?

881
00:53:47,311 --> 00:53:49,487
Is the Housemaster really
going to ask Fowler to stay on?

882
00:53:50,792 --> 00:53:52,533
Things do get about, don't they?

883
00:53:52,577 --> 00:53:54,796
-Is he?
-I don't know.

884
00:53:56,233 --> 00:53:58,278
To tell you the truth,
I don't actually care anymore.

885
00:53:59,714 --> 00:54:00,585
I've had enough.

886
00:54:01,760 --> 00:54:03,544
I haven't slept for nights
and nights.

887
00:54:04,153 --> 00:54:05,242
Really?

888
00:54:05,285 --> 00:54:06,504
Quite frankly,
I've got to the pitch

889
00:54:06,547 --> 00:54:08,027
where I wonder why we bother.

890
00:54:08,070 --> 00:54:09,115
-Who?
-Any of us.

891
00:54:09,898 --> 00:54:11,335
Why we keep
the whole thing going.

892
00:54:11,987 --> 00:54:14,120
Sometimes I think none of us
really believes in it.

893
00:54:14,381 --> 00:54:15,600
Of course you don't
believe in it.

894
00:54:16,383 --> 00:54:17,993
You're afraid to think
of anything better.

895
00:54:18,342 --> 00:54:19,560
Do you think so?

896
00:54:19,604 --> 00:54:21,606
You know perfectly well
it's all nonsense.

897
00:54:22,171 --> 00:54:23,434
You know it's positively wrong,

898
00:54:23,477 --> 00:54:24,870
but you daren't act
on your knowledge.

899
00:54:25,871 --> 00:54:27,786
You don't accept
the logical consequences.

900
00:54:28,265 --> 00:54:29,135
Is that it?

901
00:54:30,615 --> 00:54:33,226
You're afraid for your status,
your money, your class.

902
00:54:33,835 --> 00:54:36,011
Everything that makes
your life safe and comfortable

903
00:54:36,055 --> 00:54:36,925
and privileged.

904
00:54:38,405 --> 00:54:39,580
You're afraid to live
like an ordinary human being.

905
00:54:42,279 --> 00:54:43,367
Perhaps I am.

906
00:54:45,673 --> 00:54:46,587
Yes.

907
00:54:57,250 --> 00:54:58,817
Leave the window open for me,
won't you?

908
00:55:10,002 --> 00:55:11,090
My God...

909
00:55:12,178 --> 00:55:13,745
...that man's
really cracking up.

910
00:55:14,920 --> 00:55:16,530
Liberals always do
under pressure.

911
00:55:19,098 --> 00:55:19,925
You know...

912
00:55:20,969 --> 00:55:22,797
you're a really hard man, Tommy.

913
00:55:23,668 --> 00:55:24,930
I've no time for him.

914
00:55:26,540 --> 00:55:28,107
He just wants a nice easy life
with a nice easy conscience

915
00:55:28,150 --> 00:55:29,369
and he's got no right to either.

916
00:55:30,762 --> 00:55:31,937
I'm going to bed.

917
00:55:34,766 --> 00:55:36,463
Are you going to join
the fight against Fowler?

918
00:55:38,509 --> 00:55:40,511
I hate him so much,
it's difficult to be objective.

919
00:55:41,425 --> 00:55:42,861
Well, the objective
fact in this case

920
00:55:42,904 --> 00:55:45,037
is that Fowler
is absolutely objectionable.

921
00:55:51,391 --> 00:55:52,392
Please, Tommy.

922
00:55:53,437 --> 00:55:54,438
If you appeal to me
as your friend,

923
00:55:54,481 --> 00:55:55,352
I'll never forgive you.

924
00:55:56,178 --> 00:55:57,310
Menzies tried that.

925
00:55:59,747 --> 00:56:01,488
I didn't mind it from him.
He isn't a friend.

926
00:56:03,795 --> 00:56:04,970
I'll think about it, but...

927
00:56:06,363 --> 00:56:08,060
Oh, God, and I'll be in a rage
all day tomorrow.

928
00:56:10,062 --> 00:56:11,411
Ah. Jacker Pot.

929
00:56:11,672 --> 00:56:14,022
Militarism from 12
to half past four.

930
00:56:14,414 --> 00:56:16,808
Little boys all dressed up
and playing soldiers. God!

931
00:56:17,417 --> 00:56:18,287
Tommy...

932
00:56:19,332 --> 00:56:21,073
if I lose his Jacker Pot...

933
00:56:22,509 --> 00:56:24,076
...would you agree
to become a prefect then?

934
00:56:27,601 --> 00:56:28,907
If you lose his Jacker Pot,

935
00:56:28,950 --> 00:56:30,212
you probably won't be
a prefect yourself.

936
00:56:34,216 --> 00:56:36,262
-Goodnight.
-Goodnight.

937
00:56:49,536 --> 00:56:52,583
[ Foreboding music ]

938
00:58:10,269 --> 00:58:11,096
[ Sighs ]

939
00:58:29,157 --> 00:58:30,071
Guy?

940
00:58:30,811 --> 00:58:32,465
Careful! Barclay's about.

941
00:58:34,728 --> 00:58:37,383
I know. He nearly saw me.

942
00:58:38,732 --> 00:58:39,994
Thought I'd have a heart attack.

943
00:59:34,396 --> 00:59:37,399
All right, thank you, Wharton.
Now my sash.

944
01:00:15,786 --> 01:00:16,613
Good.

945
01:00:17,918 --> 01:00:18,963
Good luck, Fowler.

946
01:00:19,703 --> 01:00:20,529
Thank you, Wharton.

947
01:00:22,575 --> 01:00:23,576
Fall in!

948
01:00:49,210 --> 01:00:53,258
Battalion! Attention!

949
01:01:09,753 --> 01:01:11,493
Battalion ready
for inspection, sir.

950
01:01:11,972 --> 01:01:13,278
Thank you, sergeant major.

951
01:01:49,706 --> 01:01:50,881
How's your father?

952
01:01:50,924 --> 01:01:53,361
-Very well, thank you, sir.
-Good. Good.

953
01:02:49,113 --> 01:02:50,549
BARCLAY: Why did you do it,
Bennett?

954
01:02:50,810 --> 01:02:52,986
-BENNETT: Do what?
-You lost us the Pot!

955
01:02:53,030 --> 01:02:55,293
Oh, surely not just me,
not all on my own?

956
01:02:55,815 --> 01:02:57,425
You were far and away
the worst-dressed soldier

957
01:02:57,469 --> 01:02:58,383
on the whole parade.

958
01:02:59,776 --> 01:03:00,994
I'm not a soldier,
I'm a schoolboy and so are you.

959
01:03:01,299 --> 01:03:02,517
You're a disgrace to the house.

960
01:03:02,561 --> 01:03:04,519
You're a disgrace
to the entire school.

961
01:03:04,563 --> 01:03:06,086
Oh, I'm hopeless with Brasso.

962
01:03:06,130 --> 01:03:07,000
I can only get
a really good shine

963
01:03:07,044 --> 01:03:08,132
on my nails. Look!

964
01:03:09,220 --> 01:03:10,395
Let me see your belt!

965
01:03:11,875 --> 01:03:13,137
You want me to undress
in front of all these people?

966
01:03:13,180 --> 01:03:14,181
Give it to me!

967
01:03:16,096 --> 01:03:16,923
[ Takes off belt ]

968
01:03:22,886 --> 01:03:24,801
I reckon that's worth
a full six strokes.

969
01:03:32,634 --> 01:03:33,461
[ Sighs ]

970
01:03:34,593 --> 01:03:36,638
All right, Fowler.
You can go ahead.

971
01:03:36,682 --> 01:03:37,509
Thank you.

972
01:03:38,292 --> 01:03:39,293
Come on, Bennett.

973
01:03:39,337 --> 01:03:40,947
I appeal to Barclay
and Delahay.

974
01:03:40,991 --> 01:03:42,079
Of course.

975
01:03:42,340 --> 01:03:44,255
It's my right.
They're our House Gods.

976
01:03:44,733 --> 01:03:46,039
It won't do you any good.

977
01:03:46,910 --> 01:03:48,259
It's still my right.

978
01:03:49,390 --> 01:03:51,436
All right. If you insist.

979
01:03:51,784 --> 01:03:53,873
-If you let him off--
-We won't.

980
01:04:18,637 --> 01:04:20,639
Bennett's appealed
to House Gods.

981
01:04:20,682 --> 01:04:21,466
Gosh.

982
01:04:24,730 --> 01:04:26,253
I wonder what they'll do
to him.

983
01:04:27,559 --> 01:04:30,040
Give him a jolly good beating,
I should think.

984
01:04:35,393 --> 01:04:36,916
Well, um...

985
01:04:40,659 --> 01:04:42,922
I just thought you
ought to know...

986
01:04:44,924 --> 01:04:46,839
that if one stroke
of Fowler's cane

987
01:04:46,883 --> 01:04:48,101
lands on my ass,

988
01:04:49,537 --> 01:04:53,280
I shall go straight
to Mr. Farquharson, and, uh...

989
01:04:54,673 --> 01:04:56,805
give him the names
of all the people I've...

990
01:04:57,154 --> 01:04:58,982
...done it with
over the past three years,

991
01:04:59,025 --> 01:04:59,896
that's all.

992
01:05:03,508 --> 01:05:04,813
Bennett, you can't do this.

993
01:05:06,163 --> 01:05:07,599
Oh, I shall begin at the top.

994
01:05:09,862 --> 01:05:12,865
Well... can l, um... go now?

995
01:05:12,909 --> 01:05:14,258
Bloody little tart!

996
01:05:16,173 --> 01:05:18,218
You never thought it
particularly bloody at the time.

997
01:05:18,784 --> 01:05:20,394
My God, I'll thrash you myself!

998
01:05:20,438 --> 01:05:21,656
It's only a game, Delahay.

999
01:05:21,700 --> 01:05:23,223
There's no need
to get so excited.

1000
01:05:25,269 --> 01:05:28,098
I thought sportsmen
were supposed to be good losers.

1001
01:05:30,056 --> 01:05:32,929
[ Solemn music ]

1002
01:05:42,982 --> 01:05:44,418
I'd never have dared do that.

1003
01:05:48,292 --> 01:05:49,467
It's only cheating.

1004
01:05:51,077 --> 01:05:53,079
Everyone cheats here
the whole time.

1005
01:05:56,996 --> 01:05:58,128
I don't.

1006
01:06:00,391 --> 01:06:01,566
I bet you do.

1007
01:06:02,523 --> 01:06:03,785
When you've got the chance.

1008
01:06:07,137 --> 01:06:08,834
I don't even crib!

1009
01:06:08,877 --> 01:06:09,704
[ Sighs ]

1010
01:06:10,836 --> 01:06:12,881
I don't mean work,
I mean games.

1011
01:06:16,015 --> 01:06:17,451
Sportsmanship.

1012
01:06:20,498 --> 01:06:22,021
It's all hypocrisy.

1013
01:06:24,850 --> 01:06:27,548
Well, we all know
what goes on

1014
01:06:27,592 --> 01:06:29,202
in the scrum when
the ref's not looking.

1015
01:06:29,246 --> 01:06:30,073
[ Chuckles ]

1016
01:06:32,075 --> 01:06:33,554
Oh, well...

1017
01:06:35,165 --> 01:06:36,340
if that's what you mean.

1018
01:06:36,383 --> 01:06:37,210
Mmm.

1019
01:06:39,169 --> 01:06:40,344
Yes, of course.

1020
01:06:53,531 --> 01:06:55,054
It'll be getting light soon.

1021
01:06:55,098 --> 01:06:55,924
Mmm.

1022
01:07:00,712 --> 01:07:02,061
I must be going.

1023
01:07:15,074 --> 01:07:16,249
-[ Organ music]
-[ Choir sings ]

1024
01:07:16,554 --> 01:07:28,653
♪ I was glad when they
said unto me ♪

1025
01:07:31,743 --> 01:07:41,796
♪ We will go into
the house of the Lord ♪

1026
01:07:41,796 --> 01:07:51,719
♪ We will go into
the house of the Lord ♪

1027
01:07:57,769 --> 01:08:06,560
♪ Our feet shall stand
in thy gates ♪

1028
01:08:07,126 --> 01:08:12,392
♪ O Jerusalem

1029
01:08:14,786 --> 01:08:17,832
[ Choir continues singing hymn ]

1030
01:08:50,561 --> 01:08:52,563
[ Organ music swells ]

1031
01:08:53,999 --> 01:08:55,348
[ Scattered applause ]

1032
01:09:02,007 --> 01:09:03,487
Come on.

1033
01:09:08,405 --> 01:09:09,232
You know,

1034
01:09:10,276 --> 01:09:11,930
what I really hate
about cricket...

1035
01:09:13,018 --> 01:09:14,672
is it's such a damn good game.

1036
01:09:14,715 --> 01:09:17,805
[ Laughs ]
Ah, Judd's Paradox.

1037
01:09:18,850 --> 01:09:19,764
Of course,

1038
01:09:21,418 --> 01:09:23,463
cricket is a fundamental part
of the capitalist conspiracy,

1039
01:09:23,507 --> 01:09:24,421
hmm?

1040
01:09:24,464 --> 01:09:25,465
Of course.

1041
01:09:26,684 --> 01:09:29,774
One only has
to observe the scene.

1042
01:09:30,253 --> 01:09:33,343
There's the proletariat
forced to labor in the field

1043
01:09:33,386 --> 01:09:35,040
while the bourgeoisie

1044
01:09:35,083 --> 01:09:37,738
indulges in the pleasures
of batting and bowling.

1045
01:09:38,522 --> 01:09:39,740
Quite.

1046
01:09:39,784 --> 01:09:41,916
I mean, there's every reason
to suppose...

1047
01:09:44,963 --> 01:09:47,574
...that the game
ultimately derives

1048
01:09:47,618 --> 01:09:49,576
from the wholly
unjustified right

1049
01:09:49,620 --> 01:09:50,838
of the medieval lord

1050
01:09:50,882 --> 01:09:53,363
to the unpaid labor
of villeins and serfs

1051
01:09:53,406 --> 01:09:54,799
at haymaking and harvest.

1052
01:09:55,147 --> 01:09:57,018
You know, you're really
beginning to get the idea.

1053
01:09:57,062 --> 01:09:58,063
Thanks.

1054
01:10:00,718 --> 01:10:03,242
Ah, there he is
at the school shop.

1055
01:10:04,461 --> 01:10:06,593
[ Sighs ]
Isn't he awesome, Tommy?

1056
01:10:07,986 --> 01:10:09,509
Drawing attention
to yourself again?

1057
01:10:10,989 --> 01:10:12,469
He's not even waving back.

1058
01:10:13,209 --> 01:10:14,035
[ Scattered applause ]

1059
01:10:14,949 --> 01:10:15,776
Course he's not.

1060
01:10:16,864 --> 01:10:17,517
You should learn
from his discretion.

1061
01:10:17,822 --> 01:10:19,215
Oh, if only I could.

1062
01:10:20,520 --> 01:10:22,435
[ Violin plays ]

1063
01:10:24,307 --> 01:10:25,873
So I really can't get you
to change your mind?

1064
01:10:25,917 --> 01:10:27,397
It's not so much me,
it's my father.

1065
01:10:27,658 --> 01:10:29,573
Quite frankly, when he asked me
what I'd be staying on for,

1066
01:10:29,616 --> 01:10:30,965
it was damned hard to say.

1067
01:10:31,009 --> 01:10:32,576
You might be
on the First Eleven next term?

1068
01:10:32,619 --> 01:10:34,708
It's a long time to wait
just on the off chance.

1069
01:10:35,318 --> 01:10:37,058
If I was going to be a God,
that would be one thing but...

1070
01:10:37,755 --> 01:10:38,756
as it is...

1071
01:10:39,104 --> 01:10:40,148
just being an ordinary prefect

1072
01:10:40,192 --> 01:10:41,324
doesn't really
make it worthwhile.

1073
01:10:42,847 --> 01:10:43,674
Sorry.

1074
01:10:53,597 --> 01:10:54,511
JUDD: By the way...

1075
01:10:56,426 --> 01:10:58,079
...I've decided that
the greatest happiness

1076
01:10:58,123 --> 01:10:59,559
of the greatest number

1077
01:10:59,603 --> 01:11:02,258
will best be achieved
if I do agree to be a prefect.

1078
01:11:02,301 --> 01:11:03,259
Tommy!

1079
01:11:04,303 --> 01:11:05,130
Stop it.

1080
01:11:06,523 --> 01:11:08,220
I shall insist on the terms
set forth by Menzies

1081
01:11:08,264 --> 01:11:09,221
but with one extra condition--

1082
01:11:10,353 --> 01:11:11,397
I shall refuse
to take house prayers.

1083
01:11:11,441 --> 01:11:12,311
GUY:
Oh, he won't care about that.

1084
01:11:12,833 --> 01:11:15,314
Oh, Tommy, my cup runneth over.

1085
01:11:15,358 --> 01:11:17,577
You really are
a hero of the people.

1086
01:11:17,621 --> 01:11:19,710
I'm going to award you
the Order of Lenin,

1087
01:11:19,753 --> 01:11:21,538
first class with oak leaves.

1088
01:11:22,365 --> 01:11:24,105
You know, if I wasn't in love
with James,

1089
01:11:24,149 --> 01:11:25,716
I'd be in love with you.

1090
01:11:25,759 --> 01:11:27,283
JUDD: Don't be so emotional.
It's a purely rational decision.

1091
01:11:27,718 --> 01:11:29,067
GUY: Go on.

1092
01:11:29,110 --> 01:11:30,677
Go tell and Menzies
before you change your mind.

1093
01:11:30,721 --> 01:11:32,505
-JUDD: All right, all right.
-GUY: He's in the music school.

1094
01:11:32,549 --> 01:11:34,594
-GUY: Go on. Hurry!
-JUDD: Going, going.

1095
01:11:47,999 --> 01:11:50,001
-Wharton!
-WHARTON: Yes, Bennett?

1096
01:12:04,581 --> 01:12:06,322
Do you want to earn yourself
another ice cream?

1097
01:12:06,670 --> 01:12:07,671
I wouldn't mind.

1098
01:12:09,412 --> 01:12:10,587
If you go to school shop,

1099
01:12:10,630 --> 01:12:12,110
you'll find a man
from Longford's there--

1100
01:12:12,153 --> 01:12:13,067
Harcourt.

1101
01:12:13,111 --> 01:12:14,852
-Do you know him?
-By sight.

1102
01:12:15,287 --> 01:12:16,767
Good. Give him this.

1103
01:12:19,030 --> 01:12:20,466
Here's sixpence.

1104
01:12:24,514 --> 01:12:26,690
Why are you so keen
on Harcourt?

1105
01:12:27,430 --> 01:12:28,648
If you really don't know,

1106
01:12:28,692 --> 01:12:30,650
I'm certainly not
going to tell you.

1107
01:12:30,694 --> 01:12:31,521
Now get along.

1108
01:12:43,402 --> 01:12:44,751
-[ Gasps ]
-Oh!

1109
01:12:44,795 --> 01:12:45,970
I'll have that,
if you don't mind,

1110
01:12:46,013 --> 01:12:47,014
Wharton.

1111
01:12:47,058 --> 01:12:48,494
Now, come on!
Give it to me!

1112
01:12:52,803 --> 01:12:54,848
All right, Wharton.
Thank you.

1113
01:12:56,110 --> 01:12:57,547
Thank you very much.

1114
01:12:59,897 --> 01:13:01,942
[ Violin plays ]

1115
01:13:09,994 --> 01:13:11,125
Menzies, can I have a word?

1116
01:13:11,648 --> 01:13:12,953
Yes, of course. What is it?

1117
01:13:14,346 --> 01:13:15,956
I've decided I am willing
to become a prefect--

1118
01:13:16,000 --> 01:13:17,218
[ Shouts ]
FOWLER: Menzies!

1119
01:13:17,262 --> 01:13:18,045
...but there are one
or two some conditions--

1120
01:13:18,089 --> 01:13:18,872
Menzies!

1121
01:13:20,091 --> 01:13:21,092
Look at this.

1122
01:13:23,094 --> 01:13:23,964
What is it?

1123
01:13:26,184 --> 01:13:27,272
I've got him this time.

1124
01:13:27,751 --> 01:13:29,013
He can't get away now.

1125
01:13:29,492 --> 01:13:31,145
I'm taking this straight
to Barclay.

1126
01:13:31,929 --> 01:13:33,278
What on earth's
that all about?

1127
01:13:35,106 --> 01:13:36,586
Just one moment, Judd.

1128
01:13:37,456 --> 01:13:38,675
We can discuss this later.

1129
01:13:47,858 --> 01:13:49,903
Devenish, do you think it would
make any difference

1130
01:13:49,947 --> 01:13:50,774
to your attitude,

1131
01:13:51,383 --> 01:13:52,645
or your father's attitude,

1132
01:13:54,125 --> 01:13:55,692
if you were to tell him you were
going to be in the Gods

1133
01:13:55,735 --> 01:13:57,694
next term, instead of Bennett?

1134
01:13:58,042 --> 01:13:59,130
I'm sure it would.

1135
01:14:03,134 --> 01:14:04,788
Perhaps you should
go and telephone him.

1136
01:14:06,137 --> 01:14:07,747
You mean there's a real chance?

1137
01:14:07,791 --> 01:14:10,446
[ Solemn music ]

1138
01:14:47,178 --> 01:14:48,658
BARCLAY: Wharton!

1139
01:14:53,663 --> 01:14:55,186
[ Knocking at the door ]

1140
01:15:03,847 --> 01:15:05,501
Tell Bennett to come
to Hall Table.

1141
01:16:33,980 --> 01:16:35,025
I can't do it.

1142
01:16:35,634 --> 01:16:37,723
What's the matter?
Lost your nerve?

1143
01:16:38,681 --> 01:16:40,639
All right, I'll do it.
Come on.

1144
01:17:02,487 --> 01:17:04,620
All right, Bennett.
Bend over.

1145
01:17:20,897 --> 01:17:21,854
[ Crack ]

1146
01:17:38,218 --> 01:17:39,089
[ Crack ]

1147
01:17:45,269 --> 01:17:46,096
[ Crack ]

1148
01:17:54,104 --> 01:17:55,801
[ Crack ]

1149
01:18:00,066 --> 01:18:01,546
[ Crack ]

1150
01:18:04,810 --> 01:18:06,333
[ Crack ]

1151
01:18:09,597 --> 01:18:10,424
[ Crack ]

1152
01:19:14,662 --> 01:19:16,099
[ Sobs ]

1153
01:20:00,317 --> 01:20:01,535
I don't understand.

1154
01:20:03,494 --> 01:20:05,670
Why didn't you
just use the blackmail again?

1155
01:20:09,369 --> 01:20:10,240
Because.

1156
01:20:11,676 --> 01:20:12,590
Because what?

1157
01:20:16,594 --> 01:20:18,291
Because if I'd
gone to Housemaster...

1158
01:20:19,510 --> 01:20:21,120
it'd all come out
about James.

1159
01:20:21,686 --> 01:20:22,600
So what?

1160
01:20:26,430 --> 01:20:27,866
We'd have both been expelled.

1161
01:20:29,694 --> 01:20:30,695
Lucky you.

1162
01:20:33,089 --> 01:20:34,046
I couldn't do that.

1163
01:20:36,788 --> 01:20:38,703
-I love him.
-Oh, come on, Guy.

1164
01:20:38,746 --> 01:20:40,879
Look, I'm not going
to pretend anymore.

1165
01:20:40,923 --> 01:20:42,272
I'm sick of pretending!

1166
01:20:42,533 --> 01:20:44,187
You think it's all a joke.
Well, it's not.

1167
01:20:44,796 --> 01:20:46,363
I am never going
to love women!

1168
01:20:46,885 --> 01:20:48,104
Don't be ridiculous!

1169
01:20:49,540 --> 01:20:50,410
Martineau knew that
about himself when he was 10.

1170
01:20:50,454 --> 01:20:51,324
He told me.

1171
01:20:52,804 --> 01:20:53,892
You can't possibly know
a thing like that at 10 or now.

1172
01:20:53,936 --> 01:20:54,850
Yes, you can.

1173
01:20:56,547 --> 01:20:57,461
Look, it doesn't...

1174
01:20:58,244 --> 01:20:59,550
come as any great revelation.

1175
01:20:59,593 --> 01:21:01,900
It's... more like admitting
to yourself

1176
01:21:01,944 --> 01:21:03,249
something you've
always known.

1177
01:21:03,293 --> 01:21:05,077
Owning up to yourself. It's...

1178
01:21:06,209 --> 01:21:08,907
It's a great relief...
in some ways.

1179
01:21:09,255 --> 01:21:10,735
You can't trust intuitions
like that.

1180
01:21:10,953 --> 01:21:12,345
Well, what else is there?

1181
01:21:12,389 --> 01:21:14,782
Are you a communist
because you read Karl Marx? No.

1182
01:21:15,131 --> 01:21:16,262
You read Karl Marx

1183
01:21:16,306 --> 01:21:18,047
because you know
you are a communist.

1184
01:21:18,743 --> 01:21:20,005
Well, I'm very sorry for you.

1185
01:21:20,049 --> 01:21:21,702
Thanks! If that's
how friends react.

1186
01:21:26,838 --> 01:21:27,752
I'm sorry.

1187
01:21:30,189 --> 01:21:31,321
You're quite right.

1188
01:21:31,364 --> 01:21:32,713
That was patronizing
and unforgivable.

1189
01:21:35,238 --> 01:21:36,587
But you couldn't help it,
could you?

1190
01:21:40,330 --> 01:21:41,853
Because in your heart of hearts,

1191
01:21:41,897 --> 01:21:44,943
like Barclay and Delahay
and Fowler and Menzies,

1192
01:21:44,987 --> 01:21:46,075
you still believe...

1193
01:21:47,511 --> 01:21:48,947
in spite of your talk
of equality and fraternity,

1194
01:21:48,991 --> 01:21:50,209
you still believe...

1195
01:21:51,036 --> 01:21:53,038
some people are better
than others

1196
01:21:53,082 --> 01:21:54,518
because of the way
they make love.

1197
01:21:58,609 --> 01:22:00,654
Well...
[ Sniffs ]

1198
01:22:01,090 --> 01:22:02,743
think of that for a lifetime.

1199
01:22:05,355 --> 01:22:06,573
Think of the names.

1200
01:22:06,965 --> 01:22:11,404
Pansy. Nancy. Fairy. Fruit.
Brown nose.

1201
01:22:17,323 --> 01:22:18,150
[ Sniffs ]

1202
01:22:20,457 --> 01:22:21,632
Look, um...

1203
01:22:23,025 --> 01:22:24,765
This hurts like hell. I'm--

1204
01:22:25,984 --> 01:22:27,420
I'm-- I'm gonna walk it off.

1205
01:22:28,552 --> 01:22:29,727
Coming?

1206
01:22:35,341 --> 01:22:36,603
Good, that's settled then,
Donald.

1207
01:22:36,647 --> 01:22:37,778
Thanks.

1208
01:22:37,822 --> 01:22:40,085
I mean, well, thanks.

1209
01:22:40,390 --> 01:22:41,434
Bennett can't complain.

1210
01:22:41,478 --> 01:22:42,696
I've warned him
time and again.

1211
01:22:44,481 --> 01:22:46,962
Oh, good. Here they are.
Wonderful news.

1212
01:22:47,484 --> 01:22:49,268
Devenish is staying on
after all.

1213
01:22:51,357 --> 01:22:52,837
It's most generous of you
to offer, Judd,

1214
01:22:52,880 --> 01:22:55,318
but you can keep your principles
untarnished now.

1215
01:22:58,625 --> 01:23:00,279
But I've a disappointment
for you, Bennett,

1216
01:23:01,106 --> 01:23:02,499
though it can hardly
come as a surprise

1217
01:23:02,542 --> 01:23:03,717
after recent events.

1218
01:23:04,631 --> 01:23:06,633
I'm afraid I shall be
nominating Devenish

1219
01:23:06,677 --> 01:23:08,200
for the Gods next term
instead of you.

1220
01:23:14,990 --> 01:23:16,687
You bastard.

1221
01:23:17,209 --> 01:23:18,950
You really gave me
no choice, Guy.

1222
01:23:20,125 --> 01:23:22,475
Don't you ever call me
by my Christian name again.

1223
01:23:24,825 --> 01:23:25,652
Ever.

1224
01:23:27,089 --> 01:23:28,177
You were easily bought.

1225
01:23:28,742 --> 01:23:30,440
Well, my father was
a God himself

1226
01:23:30,483 --> 01:23:31,832
and when I told him...

1227
01:23:32,181 --> 01:23:35,010
Oh, yes, your son will be a God,
and your son's son,

1228
01:23:35,053 --> 01:23:36,315
even unto the end of school.

1229
01:23:36,359 --> 01:23:37,795
Look, we saved the house
from Fowler.

1230
01:23:38,230 --> 01:23:39,797
We saved your conscience.

1231
01:23:39,840 --> 01:23:41,364
Oh, yes.

1232
01:23:41,407 --> 01:23:43,366
All problems solved for life.
No commies and no queers.

1233
01:23:43,409 --> 01:23:44,715
Don't let's quarrel.

1234
01:23:45,107 --> 01:23:46,891
We've all got to live together
next term.

1235
01:23:47,326 --> 01:23:49,067
Let's try and do it
as amicably as possible,

1236
01:23:49,111 --> 01:23:49,937
shall we?

1237
01:24:00,513 --> 01:24:02,559
[ Bells chiming ]

1238
01:24:07,868 --> 01:24:09,174
It isn't the end of the world.

1239
01:24:13,526 --> 01:24:14,353
[ Scoffs ]

1240
01:24:17,139 --> 01:24:18,314
[ Bells continue chiming ]

1241
01:24:19,010 --> 01:24:20,011
Isn't it?

1242
01:24:23,058 --> 01:24:23,884
[ Sniffs ]

1243
01:24:25,451 --> 01:24:27,323
When people like Menzies
rule the world...

1244
01:24:30,369 --> 01:24:33,285
...and you want to be ambassador
in Paris. Hmm.

1245
01:24:34,982 --> 01:24:36,419
"Ah, Bennett, yes."

1246
01:24:37,550 --> 01:24:39,074
"Nice enough chap."

1247
01:24:40,162 --> 01:24:41,772
"Quite amusing, actually."

1248
01:24:41,815 --> 01:24:45,689
"We--We had high hopes of him
once but... oh, yes, you heard."

1249
01:24:45,732 --> 01:24:48,126
"Not--not quite one of us."

1250
01:24:49,736 --> 01:24:51,521
"Bogota, do you think?
No, maybe not."

1251
01:24:51,564 --> 01:24:53,131
"Haiti-- isn't that coming up?"

1252
01:24:53,175 --> 01:24:55,220
"That's much more his line.
You see, he was never a God."

1253
01:24:58,310 --> 01:25:00,443
"Only ever an ordinary prefect."

1254
01:25:08,059 --> 01:25:09,278
No need to be even that.

1255
01:25:15,501 --> 01:25:16,720
Oh, yes, there is.

1256
01:25:21,246 --> 01:25:23,118
If I'm spending
the rest of my life...

1257
01:25:24,510 --> 01:25:26,208
hiding my true nature...

1258
01:25:29,515 --> 01:25:32,214
I'm taking every comfort that's
going when it is going.

1259
01:25:32,257 --> 01:25:33,345
Oh, well, if that's
your attitude.

1260
01:25:34,477 --> 01:25:36,609
And, besides,
being absolutely...

1261
01:25:37,436 --> 01:25:38,655
objective...

1262
01:25:39,873 --> 01:25:41,571
it would dish me
once and for all, wouldn't it?.

1263
01:25:42,137 --> 01:25:43,747
You can't have things
both ways, Guy.

1264
01:25:43,790 --> 01:25:44,617
Why not?

1265
01:25:45,052 --> 01:25:45,879
Ow!

1266
01:25:48,969 --> 01:25:50,449
[ Whispers ]
Why not?

1267
01:25:51,233 --> 01:25:54,149
Pretend to do one thing,
only really do the other.

1268
01:25:56,716 --> 01:25:57,543
Fool the swine.

1269
01:25:59,241 --> 01:26:01,199
Play along with them.
Let them think what they like.

1270
01:26:01,243 --> 01:26:02,896
Let them despise you,
but all along--

1271
01:26:02,940 --> 01:26:04,071
Oh, don't talk dribble.

1272
01:26:05,595 --> 01:26:07,640
...and have the last laugh
and be revenged.

1273
01:26:08,119 --> 01:26:09,381
That's just sentimental twaddle.

1274
01:26:09,686 --> 01:26:11,122
You wouldn't be in the mess
you are now

1275
01:26:11,166 --> 01:26:12,210
if you had any discretion
at all.

1276
01:26:17,346 --> 01:26:19,652
What better cover
for someone like me than...

1277
01:26:20,349 --> 01:26:22,046
total indiscretion?

1278
01:26:27,356 --> 01:26:30,185
[ Wistful music ]

1279
01:26:30,707 --> 01:26:33,188
Wouldn't it be wonderful
if communism were really true?

1280
01:26:33,710 --> 01:26:34,537
It is true.

1281
01:26:37,279 --> 01:26:38,410
What? Heaven on earth?

1282
01:26:39,019 --> 01:26:39,977
Earth on earth.

1283
01:26:41,718 --> 01:26:43,198
The just earth.

1284
01:26:54,992 --> 01:26:56,689
GUY:
Of course,

1285
01:26:56,733 --> 01:26:58,996
Tommy was killed
in the Spanish Civil War.

1286
01:27:01,955 --> 01:27:03,870
Tough as old boots, Tommy was.

1287
01:27:06,264 --> 01:27:07,918
Till the bloody fascists
got him.

1288
01:27:13,576 --> 01:27:15,230
JULIE: Have you ever wanted
to go back?

1289
01:27:24,500 --> 01:27:25,327
No.

1290
01:27:26,458 --> 01:27:27,851
Is there nobody
that you'd want to see?

1291
01:27:30,070 --> 01:27:30,897
No.

1292
01:27:32,029 --> 01:27:33,639
Isn't there anything
you miss at all?

